onship|1972]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |{{flagathlete|{{sortname|Greg|Norman}}|AUS}}\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|[[1986 Open Championship|1986]], [[1993 Open Championship|1993]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |{{flagathlete|{{sortname|P\u00e1draig|Harrington}}|IRL}}\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|[[2007 Open Championship|2007]], [[2008 Open Championship|2008]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |{{flagathlete|{{sortname|Ernie|Els}}|RSA}}\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|[[2002 Open Championship|2002]], [[2012 Open Championship|2012]]\n|}\n\n===By nationality===\n{| class=\"sortable plainrowheaders wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\" \n|+Open Championship champions by nationality\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Nationality\n! scope=\"col\" | Wins\n! scope=\"col\" | Winners\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" align=left|{{USA}}\n|44\n|29\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" align=left|{{SCO}}\n|41\n|22\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" align=left|{{ENG}}\n|22\n|13\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" align=left|{{ZAF}}\n|10\n|4\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" align=left|{{AUS}}\n|9\n|4\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" align=left|{{JEY}}\n|7\n|2\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" align=left|{{NIR}}\n|3\n|3\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" align=left|{{ESP}}\n|3\n|1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" align=left|{{IRL}}\n|3\n|2\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" align=left|{{ARG}}\n|1\n|1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" align=left|{{FRA}}\n|1\n|1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" align=left|{{ITA}}\n|1\n|1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" align=left|{{NZL}}\n|1\n|1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" align=left|{{SWE}}\n|1\n|1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" align=left|{{ZWE}}\n|1\n|1\n|}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Div col|small=yes|colwidth=30em}}\n\n*{{note label|Note1|a|a}} 72 holes refers to four rounds of golf played on the same 18 holes of golf, with the pin positions varying from one round to another.\n*{{note label|Note2|b|b}} Par is a predetermined number of strokes that a golfer should require to complete a hole, a round (the sum of the total pars of the played holes), or a tournament (the sum of the total pars of each round). E stands for even, which means the tournament was completed in the predetermined number of strokes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/golf/rules_and_equipment/4230206.stm |title=Scoring |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=2008-09-20 | date=2005-09-13}}</ref>\n*{{note label|Note3|c|c}} The 1871 Open Championship was not held.<ref name=\"NotHeld\" />\n*{{note label|Note4|d|d}} Bob Martin won in a playoff against [[Davie Strath]] who refused to compete.\n*{{note label|Note5|e|e}} Willie Fernie won in a playoff against [[Bob Ferguson (golfer)|Bob Ferguson]].\n*{{note label|Note6|f|f}} Willie Park Jr. won in a playoff against [[Andrew Kirkaldy (golfer)|Andrew Kirkaldy]].\n*{{note label|Note7|g|g}} John Ball won The Open Championship as an amateur.\n*{{note label|Note8|h|h}} Harold Hilton won The Open Championship as an amateur.\n*{{note label|Note9|i|i}} Harry Vardon won in a playoff against [[John Henry Taylor]].\n*{{note label|Note10|j|j}} Harry Vardon won in a playoff against [[Arnaud Massy]].\n*{{note label|Note11|k|k}} The Open Championship was not held from 1915 to 1918 because of the [[World War I|First World War]].\n*{{note label|Note12|l|l}} Jock Hutchison won in a playoff against [[Roger Wethered]].\n*{{note label|Note13|m|m}} Bobby Jones won The Open Championship as an amateur.\n*{{note label|Note14|n|n}} Denny Shute won in a playoff against [[Craig Wood (golfer)|Craig Wood]].\n*{{note label|Note15|o|o}} The Open Championship was not held from 1940 to 1945 because of the [[World War II|Second World War]].\n*{{note label|Note16|p|p}} Bobby Locke won in a playoff against [[Harry Bradshaw (golfer)|Harry Bradshaw]].\n*{{note label|Note17|q|q}} Peter Thomson won in a playoff against [[Dave Thomas (golfer)|Dave Thomas]].\n*{{note label|Note18|r|r}} Bob Charles won in a playoff against [[Phil Rodgers]].\n*{{note label|Note19|s|s}} Jack Nicklaus won in a playoff against [[Doug Sanders]].\n*{{note label|Note20|t|t}} Tom Watson won in a playoff against [[Jack Newton]].\n*{{note label|Note21|u|u}} Mark Calcavecchia won in a playoff against [[Wayne Grady]] and [[Greg Norman]].\n*{{note label|Note22|v|v}} John Daly won in a playoff against [[Costantino Rocca]].\n*{{note label|Note23|w|w}} Mark O'Meara won in a playoff against [[Brian Watts]].\n*{{note label|Note24|x|x}} Paul Lawrie won in a playoff against [[Jean van de Velde (golfer)|Jean van de Velde]] and [[Justin Leonard]].\n*{{note label|Note25|y|y}} Ernie Els won in a playoff against [[Thomas Levet]], [[Steve Elkington]] and [[Stuart Appleby]].\n*{{note label|Note26|z|z}} Todd Hamilton won in a playoff against [[Ernie Els]].\n*{{note label|Note27|aa|aa}} P\u00e1draig Harrington won in a playoff against [[Sergio Garc\u00eda]].\n*{{note label|Note28|bb|bb}} Stewart Cink won in a playoff against [[Tom Watson (golfer)|Tom Watson]].\n*{{note label|Note29|cc|cc}} Zach Johnson won in a playoff against [[Marc Leishman]] and [[Louis Oosthuizen]].\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n'''General'''\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.opengolf.com/~/media/The%20Open/Information/Media_Guide.ashx |title=2011 Open Championship Media Guide |publisher=The Open Championship |accessdate=2011-08-20 |format=PDF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110806084256/http://www.opengolf.com/~/media/The%20Open/Information/Media_Guide.ashx |archivedate=2011-08-06 }}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.opengolf.com/en/History/OpenChampions.aspx |title=Open Champions |publisher=The Open Championship |accessdate=2011-08-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100302213551/http://www.opengolf.com/en/History/OpenChampions.aspx |archivedate=2010-03-02 }}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.opengolf.com/en/History/PreviousOpens.aspx |title=Previous Opens |publisher=The Open Championship |accessdate=2011-08-20 }}\n'''Specific'''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.opengolf.com/ The Open Championship official site]\n*[http://www.randa.org/ R&A website]\n\n{{The Open champions}}\n{{The Open Championships}}\n{{Open Championship Courses}}\n{{Major Champions}}\n\n{{featured list}}\n\n[[Category:The Open Championship|*List]]\n[[Category:Lists of male golfers|Open Champ]]\n[[Category:Winners of men's major golf championships|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n[[Image:HarryVardon.jpg|thumb|200px|right|[[Harry Vardon]], six-time Open Champion in 1896, 1898, 1899, 1903, 1911, and 1914, which is a record]]\n\n[[The Open Championship]] is an annual [[golf]] competition held in the [[United Kingdom]] that was established in 1860.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.opengolf.com/ChampionshipGolf/TheOpenChampionship/History/PreviousOpens.aspx?eventid=1860000 |title=Prestwick - 1860 |publisher=[[The Open Championship|Open Golf]] |accessdate=2008-09-12 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> It is played on the weekend of the third Friday in July, and is the third of the four [[Men's major golf championships|major championships]] to be played each year.<ref>{{cite book|author=Stuart Newport|title=Guinness Book Of Knowledge |publisher=Guinness Publishing |pages=272 |year=1997 |isbn=0-85112-046-6 }}</ref> In addition, this championship is conducted by [[The Royal and Ancient Golf Club of St Andrews]] (R&A). The championship was not held in 1871 due to a disagreement over a new trophy,<ref name=\"NotHeld\">{{cite web |url=http://www.opengolf.com/ChampionshipGolf/TheOpenChampionship/History/ClaretJug.aspx |title=Claret Jug |publisher=[[The Open Championship|Open Golf]] |accessdate=2009-07-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090718075849/http://www.opengolf.com/ChampionshipGolf/TheOpenChampionship/History/ClaretJug.aspx |archivedate=2009-07-18 }}</ref> and from 1915 to 1919 and from 1940 to 1945 due to the [[World War I|First]] and [[World War II|Second]] World Wars respectively.\n\nThe reigning champion of the competition is automatically invited to play in the other three majors ([[Masters Tournament|Masters]], the [[U.S. Open (golf)|U.S. Open]], and the [[PGA Championship]]) for the next five years. The prize of the tournament is the Golf Champion Trophy, commonly known as the [[Claret Jug]], and the champion personally keeps the trophy until the next competition the following year. The champion also receives a gold medal, which they are allowed to keep permanently. Until 1870 the champion received the Challenge Belt, however when Tom Morris Jr. (more commonly known as [[Young Tom Morris]]) won the Open Championship three times in a row he won the belt outright, necessitating the need for a new trophy.<ref name=\"NotHeld\"/>\n\n[[Harry Vardon]] holds the record for the most Open Championship victories, winning six times during his career. The oldest winner of the Open Championship is Tom Morris Sr. (or [[Old Tom Morris]]) who was {{age in years and days|16 Jun 1821|26 Sep 1867|sep=and}} old when he won in [[1867 Open Championship|1867]]. His son, Tom Morris Jr., is the youngest winner of the championship, he was {{age in years and days|20 Apr 1851|23 Sep 1868|sep=and}} old when he won the [[1868 Open Championship]]. He also won the most consecutive times with four victories (1868\u20131872). [[Henrik Stenson]] holds the dual distinction of being both the most strokes under [[Par (score)|par]] for 72 holes (\u221220) and also recording the lowest total score (264) when he won in [[2016 Open Championship|2016]].\n\n==Champions==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Key\n|''(n/a)''\n|Information not available\n|-\n|width=\"40px\" align=center style=\"background-color:#cedff2\"|{{dagger|alt=Tournament won in a playoff}}\n|Tournament won in a [[Playoff (golf)|playoff]]\n|-\n|width=\"40px\" align=center style=\"background-color:#FBCEB1\"|*\n|Tournament won by an [[amateur]]\n|}\n\n===By year===\n[[File:James Braid (golfer) 1913.jpg|thumb|upright|right|[[James Braid (golfer)|James Braid]], five-time Open Champion in 1901, 1905, 1906, 1908, and 1910]]\n[[Image:JohnHenryTaylor.jpg|thumb|upright|right|[[John Henry Taylor]], five-time Open Champion in 1894, 1895, 1900, 1909, 1913]]\n[[File:2008 Open Championship - Tom Watson.jpg|thumb|upright|right|[[Tom Watson (golfer)|Tom Watson]], five-time Open Champion in 1975, 1977, 1980, 1982, 1983]]\n[[Image:Old and Young Tom Morris.jpg|thumb|upright|right|[[Old Tom Morris|Tom Morris Sr.]], four-time Open Champion in 1861, 1862, 1864, and 1867.<br>[[Young Tom Morris|Tom Morris Jr.]], four-time Open Champion in 1868, 1869, 1870, and 1872.]]\n[[File:Willie Park Senior wearing the Championship Belt.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Willie Park Sr.]], four-time Open Champion in 1860, 1863, 1866, and 1875]]\n[[Image:Walter Hagen 1914.png|thumb|upright|right|[[Walter Hagen]], four-time Open Champion in 1922, 1924, 1928, and 1929]]\n[[Image:1880-82 Open Champion Bob Ferguson.jpg|thumb|upright|right|[[Bob Ferguson (golfer)|Bob Ferguson]], three-time Open Champion in 1880, 1881, 1882]]\n[[File:BobbyJonesAge14.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Bobby Jones (golfer)|Bobby Jones]], three-time Open Champion in 1926, 1927, and 1930.  He is one of six champions to win wire-to-wire after 72-holes played with his victory in 1927.]]\n[[File:Henry-Cotton 1931.jpg|thumb|upright|right|[[Henry Cotton (golfer)|Henry Cotton]], three-time Open Champion in 1934, 1937, and 1948.  He is one of six champions to win wire-to-wire after 72-holes played with his victory in 1934.]]\n[[File:All Black.jpg|thumb|upright|right|[[Gary Player]], three-time Open Champion in 1959, 1968, and 1974.]]\n[[Image:JackNicklaus.cropped.jpg|thumb|upright|right|[[Jack Nicklaus]], three-time Open Champion in 1966, 1970, and 1978]]\n[[Image:Seve Ballesteros 2006-07-19.jpg|thumb|upright|right|[[Seve Ballesteros]], three-time Open Champion in 1979, 1984, and 1988]]\n[[File:Nick Faldo.jpg|thumb|upright|right|[[Nick Faldo]], three-time Open Champion in 1987, 1990, and 1992]]\n[[File:Tiger Woods drives by Allison.jpg|thumb|upright|right|[[Tiger Woods]], three-time Open Champion in 2000, 2005, and 2006.  He is one of six champions to win wire-to-wire after 72-holes played with his victory in 2005.]]\n{| class=\"sortable plainrowheaders wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|+The Open Championship champions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Country\n! scope=\"col\" | Champion\n! scope=\"col\" | Course\n! scope=\"col\" | Location\n! scope=\"col\" | Total score\n! scope=\"col\" | To [[Par (score)|par]]{{ref label|Note2|b|b}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[1860 Open Championship|1860]]\n|{{SCO}}\n|{{sortname|Willie|Park Sr.||Park, Willie Sr.}}\n|[[Prestwick Golf Club]]\n|{{sort|Scotland, Prestwick|[[Prestwick]], [[Scotland]]}}\n|align=center|174\n|align=center|''n/a''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" |[[1861 Open Championship|1861]]\n|{{SCO}}\n|{{sortname|Tom|Morris Sr.|Old Tom Morris}}\n|[[Prestwick Golf Club]]\n|{{sort|Scotland, Prestwick|[[Prestwick]], [[Scotland]]}}\n|align=center|163\n|align=center|''n/a''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" |[[1862 Open Championship|1862]]\n|{{SCO}}\n|{{sortname|Tom|Morris Sr.|Old Tom Morris}}\n|[[Prestwick Golf Club]]\n|{{sort|Scotland, Prestwick|[[Prestwick]], [[Scotland]]}}\n|align=center|163\n|align=center|''n/a''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" |[[1863 Open Championship|1863]]\n|{{SCO}}\n|{{sortname|Willie|Park Sr.||Park, Willie Sr.}}\n|[[Prestwick Golf Club]]\n|{{sort|Scotland, Prestwick|[[Prestwick]], [[Scotland]]}}\n|align=center|168\n|align=center|''n/a''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" |[[1864 Open Championship|1864]]\n|{{SCO}}\n|{{sortname|Tom|Morris Sr.|Old Tom Morris}}\n|[[Prestwick Golf Club]]\n|{{sort|Scotland, Prestwick|[[Prestwick]], [[Scotland]]}}\n|align=center|167\n|align=center|''n/a''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" |[[1865 Open Championship|1865]]\n|{{SCO}}\n|{{sortname|Andrew|Strath}}\n|[[Prestwick Golf Club]]\n|{{sort|Scotland, Prestwick|[[Prestwick]], [[Scotland]]}}\n|align=center|162\n|align=center