}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{Newport County A.F.C. squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:King, Tom}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Plymouth]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:England youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:English people of Welsh descent]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:Portsmouth F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Crystal Palace F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Millwall F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Welling United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Braintree Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Stevenage F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Newport County A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:National League (English football) players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMillwall:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_King_(footballer)"}
{"title_page": "Ned Lamont", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{good article}}\n{{short description|89th Governor of Connecticut}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Ned Lamont\n|image       = Governor Ned Lamont of Connecticut, official portrait.jpg\n|order       = 89th [[List of governors of Connecticut|Governor of Connecticut]]\n|lieutenant  = [[Susan Bysiewicz]]\n|term_start  = January 9, 2019\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[Dannel Malloy|Dan Malloy]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_name  = Edward Miner Lamont Jr.\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1954|1|3}}\n|birth_place = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse      = {{marriage|[[Ann Lamont|Ann Huntress]]|September 10, 1983}}\n|children    = 3\n|residence   = [[Connecticut Governor's Residence|Governor's Mansion]] \n|education   = [[Harvard University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Yale University]] ([[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])\n|website     = {{url|portal.ct.gov/Office-of-the-Governor|Government website}}\n}}\n'''Edward Miner Lamont Jr.''' (born January 3, 1954) is an American businessman and politician serving as the [[List of governors of Connecticut|89th governor of Connecticut]] since January 9, 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://greenwich.dailyvoice.com/neighbors/happy-birthday-to-greenwichs-ned-lamont-jr/552594/|title=Happy Birthday to Greenwich's Ned Lamont Jr.|work=Greenwich Daily Voice|date=January 3, 2014|accessdate=August 15, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Courant2018Win\">{{cite news|last1=Vigdor|first1=Neil|last2=Kovner|first2=Josh|last3=Lender|first3=Jon|last4=Ormseth|first4=Matthew|last5=Megan|first5=Kathleen|last6=Rondinone|first6=Nicholas|title=Bob Stefanowski Concedes Governor's Race After Cities Push Ned Lamont To Victory|url=https://www.courant.com/politics/elections/hc-election-governor-connecticut-lamont-stefanowski-20181101-story.html|work=[[Hartford Courant]]|date=November 7, 2018|accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref> A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], he served as a [[Greenwich, Connecticut|Greenwich]] selectman from 1987 to 1989. He ran for the [[U.S. Senate]] in [[2006 United States Senate election in Connecticut|2006]], defeating incumbent Senator [[Joe Lieberman]] in the state Democratic primary election, but was defeated in the general election by Lieberman, who then ran as a [[Connecticut for Lieberman|third-party]] candidate.<ref name=Lamont2018/>\n\nLamont then ran for governor in [[2010 Connecticut gubernatorial election|2010]], but was defeated in the Democratic primary by former [[Stamford, Connecticut|Stamford]] [[Mayor of Stamford, Connecticut|mayor]] [[Dannel Malloy|Dan Malloy]], who went on to win the general election. Lamont ran again in [[2018 Connecticut gubernatorial election|2018]], winning the party nomination and defeating Republican [[Bob Stefanowski]] in the general election.<ref name=Lamont2018>{{cite web|last=Blair|first=Russell|url=http://www.courant.com/politics/hc-pol-ned-lamont-governors-race-20180117-story.html|title=Ned Lamont Jumps Into Connecticut Governor's Race|work=[[Hartford Courant]]|date=January 17, 2018|accessdate=January 17, 2018}}</ref> He uses his nickname '''Ned''' in his official capacity as governor, as he has done throughout his public life.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.courant.com/politics/capitol-watch/hc-pol-edward-ned-lamont-20181212-story.html|title=Ned or Edward? Lamont keeps it informal as governor|first=Daniela|last=Altimari|date=December 12, 2018|accessdate=June 10, 2019|work=Hartford Courant}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nLamont was born on January 3, 1954, in [[Washington, D.C.]], to Camille Helene (n\u00e9e Buzby) and Edward Miner Lamont. His mother was born in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]] to parents from the U.S. mainland, and later worked as a staffer for Senator [[Estes Kefauver]].<ref name=\"Legacy\">{{cite news|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/nytimes/obituary.aspx?pid=173841282 |title=Camille Lamont Obituary|newspaper=The New York Times|date=January 14, 2015|accessdate=October 9, 2016}}</ref> His father, an economist, worked on the [[Marshall Plan]] and then served in the [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development|Department of Housing and Urban Development]] during the [[Presidency of Richard Nixon|Nixon administration]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenation.com/article/fight-partys-soul|title=A Fight for the Party's Soul|first=John|last=Nichols|work=[[The Nation]]|date=July 27, 2006|accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> He is the great-grandson of former [[J. P. Morgan & Co.]] chair [[Thomas W. Lamont]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wargs.com/other/lamont.html|title=Ancestry of Ned Lamont|first=William Addams|last=Reitwiesner|accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the40yearplan.com/article_012406.php|work=The 40-Year Plan|title=Ned Lamont (interview)|first=Ken|last=Krayeske|date=January 24, 2006|accessdate=August 5, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070225081606/http://www.the40yearplan.com/article_012406.php|archivedate=February 25, 2007}}</ref> and a grand-nephew of former [[American Civil Liberties Union]] director [[Corliss Lamont]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.corliss-lamont.org/|title=The Life of Corliss Lamont|date=May 27, 2018|accessdate=August 15, 2018|publisher=Half-Moon Foundation, Inc.}}</ref> He is a distant descendant of colonial diarist [[Thomas Minor]], from whom he gets his middle name.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/15/opinion/nyregionopinions/15CT_Sleeper.html|title=The American Lamonts|work=The New York Times|first=Jim|last=Sleeper|accessdate=February 27, 2019|date=October 15, 2006}}</ref>{{efn|The spelling of Minor's [[surname]] has historically varied between ''Minor'' and ''Miner''.<ref name=Curious>Miner, John A. and Miner, Robert F. \"The Curious Pedigree of Lt. Thomas Minor\". ''New England Historical and Genealogical Register''. New England Historic Genealogical Society. July 1984, pg 182-185. Accessed 14 July 2007.</ref>\n}}\n\nLamont's family moved to [[Laurel Hollow, New York|Laurel Hollow]] on [[Long Island]] when he was seven years old.{{efn|Some media outlets erroneously report Lamont's childhood home as [[Syosset, New York]] due to its shared [[ZIP Code]] (11791) with Laurel Hollow.<ref name=\"Kershaw\"/><ref name=\"Legacy\"/>}} The eldest of three children, he and his sisters attended [[East Woods School]].<ref name=\"Legacy\"/><ref name=\"Kershaw\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/01/nyregion/01lamont.html|title=A Son of Privilege Takes His Baby Steps on the Political Proving Ground|work=The New York Times|first1=Sarah|last1=Kershaw|first2=Alison Leigh|last2=Cowan|date=November 1, 2006|accessdate=November 9, 2018}}</ref> He later attended [[Phillips Exeter Academy]], and served as president of the student newspaper, ''[[The Exonian]]''. After graduating from Phillips Exeter in 1972, he earned a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[sociology]] from [[Harvard College]] in 1976 and a [[Master of Business Administration]] from the [[Yale School of Management]] in 1980.<ref name=\"Kershaw\"/><ref name=\"CT mirror\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ctmirror.org/node/6058/candidate|title=Ned Lamont: Democrat candidate for Governor|work=[[The Connecticut Mirror]]|accessdate=August 5, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100704084345/http://www.ctmirror.org/node/6058/candidate|archivedate=July 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nIn 1977, Lamont became editor for the ''[[Black River Tribune]]'', a small weekly newspaper in [[Ludlow (village), Vermont|Ludlow, Vermont]]. During his time there, he worked alongside journalists [[Jane Mayer]] and [[Alex Beam]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.courant.com/2010-08-02/news/hc-primary-gov-ned-lamont-0803-20100802_1_stamford-mayor-dannel-malloy-bitter-race-republicans-and-democrats|title=Unknown No Longer, Lamont Runs For Governor|first=Christopher|last=Keating|newspaper=Hartford Courant|date=August 2, 2010|accessdate=August 28, 2018}}</ref> After graduating from Yale, he entered the cable television industry, managing the startup operation in [[Fairfield County, Connecticut]] for [[Cablevision]].<ref name=\"CT mirror\"/> In 1984, he founded Campus Televideo, a company that provides cable and satellite services to college campuses across the United States.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hartfordbusiness.com/article/20180720/NEWHAVENBIZ/180729989/lamont-in-the-lions-den|title=Lamont in the lion's den|work=New Haven Biz|date=July 20, 2018|first=Michael C.|last=Bingham|accessdate=August 29, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Keating>{{cite news|url=http://www.courant.com/politics/capitol-watch/hc-pol-lamont-sold-cable-tv-company-20180119-story.html|title=After Selling Cable Company, Ned Lamont is 'All In'|first=Christopher|last=Keating|newspaper=Hartford Courant|date=January 19, 2018|accessdate=August 29, 2018}}</ref> He later chaired Lamont Digital Systems, a telecommunications firm that invests in [[new media]] startups.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/profiles/companies/9889540Z:US-lamont-digital-systems-inc|title=Lamont Digital Systems Inc|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=August 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctpost.com/politics/article/Ned-Lamont-s-cable-business-had-an-MTV-13111577.php|title=Ned Lamont's cable business launched with tip from MTV|first=Dan|last=Haar|newspaper=Connecticut Post|date=July 28, 2018|accessdate=August 28, 2018}}</ref> Campus Televideo was its largest division before [[Austin, Texas]]-based firm Apogee acquired it on September 3, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marketwired.com/press-release/apogee-acquires-campus-televideo-becomes-higher-educations-largest-resnet-video-solutions-2052678.htm|title=Apogee Acquires Campus Televideo -- Becomes Higher Education's Largest ResNet and Video Solutions Provider|date=September 3, 2015|work=Market Wired}}</ref><ref name=Keating/>\n\nLamont has served on the [[board of trustees]] for the [[Conservation Services Group]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nedlamont.com/about|title=About Ned|accessdate=November 29, 2018|publisher=Ned for CT}}</ref> [[Mercy Corps]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mercycorps.org/articles/iraq/ned-lamont-calls-out-mercy-corps-work-huffington-post|title=Ned Lamont calls out Mercy Corps' work on The Huffington Post|work=Mercy Corps|first=Joy|last=Portella|date=June 30, 2009|accessdate=August 29, 2018}}</ref> the [[Norman Rockwell Museum]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrm.org/2011/09/norman-rockwell-museum-announces-new-board-members/|title=Norman Rockwell Museum Announces New Board Members|work=[[Norman Rockwell Museum]]|date=September 9, 2011|accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> the [[YMCA]], and the [[Young Presidents' Organization]].<ref name=\"moffly\">{{cite web|url=https://ilovefc.com/2006/04/19/ned-lamont-makes-a-run-for-the-us-senate/|title=Ned Lamont Makes a Run for the US Senate|date=April 19, 2006|publisher=Moffly Media|website=ilovefc.com|accessdate=August 15, 2018}}</ref> He has also served on the advisory boards of the [[Yale School of Management]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://som.yale.edu/community/school-leadership-boards/boards-councils/yale-som-board-of-advisors|title=Yale SOM Board of Advisors|work=Yale School of Management|publisher=Yale University|accessdate=August 15, 2018}}</ref> and the [[Brookings Institution]].<ref name=\"moffly\"/>\n\n==Early political career==\n{{see also|Electoral history of Ned Lamont}}\nLamont was first elected in 1987 as a [[selectman]] in [[Greenwich, Connecticut]], where he served for one term. He ran for [[Connecticut Senate|state senate]] in 1990, where he faced Republican William Nickerson and incumbent senator Emil \"Bennie\" Benvenuto (who had switched his party affiliation from Republican to [[A Connecticut Party]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.courant.com/politics/capitol-watch/hc-greenwich-mourns-death-of-former-sen-bennie-benvenuto-ran-against-ned-lamont-and-bill-nickerson-in-1990-senate-race-20111012-story.html|title=Greenwich Mourns Death Of Former Sen. Bennie Benvenuto; Ran Against Ned Lamont And Bill Nickerson In Three-Way 1990 State Senate Race|work=Hartford Courant|first=Christopher|last=Keating|date=October 12, 2011|accessdate=January 2, 2019}}</ref> Nickerson won the three-way race with Lamont finishing in third place.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=697193|publisher=Our Campaigns|title=CT State Senate 36|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref> Lamont later served for three terms on the Greenwich town finance board and chaired the State Investment Advisory Council, which oversees state pension fund investments. During his term as chair, the state saw its unfunded liabilities reduced and pension fund performance improved.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myleftnutmeg.com/showDiary.do?diaryId=237|work=MyLeftNutmeg|title=Lamont Grants MyLeftNutmeg First Blogger Interview|date=January 13, 2006|accessdate=August 3, 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060613193545/http://www.myleftnutmeg.com/showDiary.do?diaryId=237|archivedate=June 13, 2006}}</ref>\n\n===2006 U.S. Senate election===\n{{main|2006 United States Senate election in Connecticut}}\n[[File:United States Senate election results in Connecticut by municipality, 2006.svg|thumb|General election results by municipality. Shades of blue denote win for Lamont, yellow for Lieberman.]]\n[[File:NedLamont2006.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Lamont in 2006.]]\n[[File:Ned Lamont YearlyKos 2007 (1000450845).jpg|thumb|220px|Lamont attending the [[Netroots Nation#2007|2007 YearlyKos]] conference at the [[McCormick Place]] in [[Chicago]].]]\nOn March 13, 2006, Lamont announced his campaign for the U.S. Senate against incumbent [[Joe Lieberman]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yaledailynews.com/blog/2006/04/06/lamont-courts-local-voters/|title=Lamont courts local voters|first=Melina|last=Cordero|date=April 6, 2006|accessdate=February 8, 2013|work=[[Yale Daily News]]}}</ref>\n\nOn July 6, Lamont faced off against Lieberman in a televised debate that covered issues such as the [[Iraq War]], energy policy, and [[immigration]]. During the debate, Lieberman argued he was being subjected to a [[Litmus test (politics)|litmus test]] on the war, insisted he was a \"bread-and-butter Democrat,\" and on many occasions asked, \"who is Ned Lamont?\" Lieberman then asked Lamont if he would release his [[income tax]] returns, which he did afterwards.<ref name=NBCFaceOff>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbc30.com/politics/9481028/detail.html|title=Lieberman, Lamont Face Off In NBC 30 Debate|work=[[WVIT]]|date=July 6, 2006|accessdate=August 5, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071225190159/http://www.nbc30.com/politics/9481028/detail.html|archivedate=December 25, 2007}}</ref>\n\nLamont focused on Lieberman's supportive relationship with Republicans, telling him \"if you won't challenge [[George W. Bush|President Bush]] and his failed agenda, I will.\" He criticized Lieberman's vote for the [[Energy Policy Act of 2005]], which he dubbed the \"Bush-[[Dick Cheney|Cheney]]-Lieberman energy bill.\" In response to the assertion that he supported Republican policies, Lieberman stated he had voted with [[Senate Democratic Caucus|Senate Democrats]] 90% of the time. Lamont argued the three-term incumbent lacked the courage to challenge the [[Presidency of George W. Bush|Bush administration]] on the Iraq War.<ref name=\"NBCFaceOff\"/> He also criticized Lieberman for supporting federal intervention in the [[Terri Schiavo case]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://inthesetimes.com/article/2549/why_ned_lamont_is_a_democrat|title=Why Ned Lamont is a Democrat|date=March 21, 2006|last=Seder|first=Sam|accessdate=August 15, 2018|work=In These Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.truthdig.com/articles/ned-lamont-the-truthdig-interview/|title=Ned Lamont: The Truthdig Interview|last=Golson|first=Blair|date=April 26, 2006|accessdate=August 15, 2018|work=TruthDig}}</ref>\n\nOn July 30, ''[[The New York Times]]'' editorial board endorsed Lamont.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/30/opinion/30sun1.html?_r=1&oref=slogin|title=A Senate Race in Connecticut|date=July 30, 2006|accessdate=August 15, 2018|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> That same day, ''[[The Sunday Times (UK)|The Sunday Times]]'' reported former President [[Bill Clinton]] warned Lieberman not to run as an independent if he lost the primary to Lamont.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/the-anti-war-tycoon-splits-democrats-k0fq0w57gfl|work=[[The Sunday Times (UK)|The Sunday Times]]|title=The anti-war tycoon splits Democrats|first=Tony|last=Allen-Mills|date=July 30, 2006|accessdate=August 3, 2006}}</ref> Pledging to refuse money from [[lobbyist]]s during the election, Lamont funded most of his own campaign, with donations exceeding $12.7 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/10/21/AR2006102101016.html|title=Lamont Gives $2M to Flagging Campaign|first=Andrew|last=Miga|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=October 21, 2006|accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://lamontblog.blogspot.com/2006/04/4000-donors-in-first-quarter.html|title=4,000 Donors in First Quarter|date=April 3, 2006|accessdate=August 5, 2013|work=LamontBlog|first=Ned|last=Lamont}}</ref>\n\nLamont won the primary with 52% of the vote<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/files/elections/2006/by_state/CT_Page_0808.html?SITE=CTHARELN&SECTION=POLITICS|title=Connecticut primary results|newspaper=Hartford Courant|date=August 10, 2006|accessdate=August 5, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130325075023/http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/files/elections/2006/by_state/CT_Page_0808.html?SITE=CTHARELN&SECTION=POLITICS|archivedate=March 25, 2013}}</ref> (this was the only [[2006 United States Senate elections|Senate race in 2006]] where an incumbent lost re-nomination). In his concession speech, Lieberman announced he was standing by his earlier statements that he would run as an independent if he lost the Democratic primary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/14228351/#.URRQYGdU5co|title=Lieberman concedes; Lamont wins primary|date=August 9, 2006|accessdate=February 8, 2013|work=[[NBC News]]}}</ref> Running under the banner of [[Connecticut for Lieberman]], Lieberman won the general election with nearly 50% of the vote (exit polls showed Lieberman won 33% of Democrats, 54% of independents, and 70% of Republicans).<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/ELECTION/2006/pages/results/states/CT/S/01/epolls.0.html|work=[[CNN]]|title=America Votes 2006: Exit Polls|accessdate=August 5, 2013}}</ref> The [[Sundance TV|Sundance Channel]] documentary film ''[[Blog Wars]]'' chronicled the influence [[political blogging]] had on the election.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.powerlineblog.com/archives/2006/12/016037.php|first=John|last=Hinderaker|date=December 26, 2006|accessdate=March 4, 2019|title=Blog Wars|work=Power Line}}</ref>\n\nWhile some [[Research 2000]] polls commissioned by the [[Daily Kos]] in 2007 and 2008 found he would win a Senate rematch with Lieberman by growing margins,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailykos.com/story/2008/04/07/491459/-CT-Sen-Lieberman-s-popularity-continues-to-slide|work=[[Daily Kos]]|title=CT-Sen: Lieberman's popularity continues to slide|date=April 7, 2008|accessdate=August 5, 2013|first=Markos|last=Moulitsas}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/campaigns/43974-poll-lieberman-would-lose-to-lamont|title=Poll: Lieberman Would Lose to Lamont|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|first=Walter|last=Alarkon|date=July 6, 2008|accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> Lamont stated he was not considering another campaign for Senate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctmirror.org/story/2010/12/07/lamont-not-looking-rematch-lieberman-2012|title=Lamont not looking for a rematch with Lieberman in 2012|work=Connecticut Mirror|first=Mark|last=Pazniokas|date=December 8, 2010|accessdate=August 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2008 presidential campaign activity===\nLamont initially supported [[Chris Dodd]]'s [[Chris Dodd 2008 presidential campaign|presidential campaign]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/ari-melber/ned-lamont-backs-habeas-c_b_42069.html|title=Ned Lamont Backs Habeas Corpus- and Chris Dodd|first=Ari|last=Melber|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=February 25, 2007|accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071225193654/http://www.thepolitic.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=77&Itemid=38|title=\"Ned Who\" No More: An interview with Ned Lamont|first=Christopher|last=Gombeski|date=November 10, 2007|accessdate=August 15, 2008|work=The Politic}}</ref> After Dodd dropped out of the race, Lamont became a state co-chair for [[Barack Obama]]'s [[Barack Obama 2008 presidential campaign|presidential campaign]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/ned-lamont/why-im-supporting-barack_b_80986.html|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|first=Ned|last=Lamont|title=Why I'm Supporting Barack Obama|date=March 28, 2008|accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> Obama's victory in the [[2008 Connecticut Democratic primary|Connecticut Democratic primary]] was credited to Lamont's ability to turn out the voter base he had built during his Senate campaign.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/06/us/politics/06region.html?ref=nyregion|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=Obama Takes Connecticut, Helped by Lamont Voters|first=David W.|last=Chen|date=February 6, 2008|accessdate=May 20, 2010}}</ref> In March 2008, he was elected as a state delegate to the [[2008 Democratic National Convention]], his support pledged to Obama.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thegreenpapers.com/P08/CT-D.phtml|work=The Green Papers|title=Connecticut Democratic Delegation 2008|date=February 5, 2008|accessdate=July 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Academic career==\n[[File:Ned Lamont and Merle Harris (2557042728) (cropped).jpg|thumb|220px|Lamont speaking with former CCSU president Merle Harris in June 2008.]]\nBefore the 2006 election, Lamont had volunteered at [[Warren Harding High School]] in [[Bridgeport, Connecticut|Bridgeport]], where he focused on teaching entrepreneurship and coordinating internships with local businesses.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctpost.com/news/article/Testing-Lamont-s-ties-to-Harding-High-12991863.php|title=Fact checking Lamont's ties to Harding High||first=Brian|last=Lockhart|date=June 13, 2018|work=Connecticut Post|accessdate=October 29, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"CONEG\">{{cite web|url=https://www.coneg.org/governor/ned-lamont/|title=Edward Miner \u201cNed\u201d Lamont, Jr., Connecticut Governor|work=Coalition of Northeastern Governors|accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref>  After the election, he served as a teaching [[fellow]] at the [[Harvard Institute of Politics]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iop.harvard.edu/former-fellows/L|title=Former Fellows-The Institute of Politics|work=[[Harvard Institute of Politics]]|accessdate=February 8, 2013|publisher=[[Harvard University]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022154552/http://www.iop.harvard.edu/former-fellows/L|archivedate=October 22, 2012}}</ref> and the Yale School of Management. He then became an adjunct faculty member and chair of the Arts and Sciences Public Policy Committee at [[Central Connecticut State University]] (CCSU), where he was named Distinguished Professor of Political Science and Philosophy.<ref name=\"CONEG\"/> During his time at CCSU, he was a [[lecturer]] in multiple classes and founded a business startup competition.<ref name=\"CONEG\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctpost.com/politics/article/Ned-Lamont-s-eight-year-break-from-politics-13321174.php|title=Ned Lamont\u2019s eight-year break from politics|date=October 21, 2018|first=Kaitlyn|last=Krasselt|work=CT Post|accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref> In 2019, he delivered the [[commencement speech]] for CCSU, his first as governor.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.apnews.com/a358fc64e1924613bd18ac8c9029d11e|title=Gov. Ned Lamont to deliver commencement remarks at CCSU|date=May 12, 2019|work=Associated Press|accessdate=June 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Governor of Connecticut (2019\u2013present)==\n===Elections===\n====2010====\n{{main|2010 Connecticut gubernatorial election}}\nOn February 16, 2010, Lamont announced his candidacy for the [[2010 Connecticut gubernatorial election|2010 gubernatorial election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ctmirror.org/2010/02/16/lamont-announces-governor-pitching-himself-outsider/|title=Lamont announces for governor, pitching himself as an outsider|first=Mark|last=Pazniokas|work=[[Connecticut Mirror]]|date=February 16, 2010|accessdate=August 29, 2010}}</ref> Former [[Stamford, Connecticut|Stamford]] mayor [[Dannel Malloy|Dan Malloy]] defeated him at the state Democratic convention on May 22, receiving 1,232 votes (68%) to Lamont's 582 votes (32%). Since he won more than 15% of the vote, Lamont was eligible to appear on the primary election ballot.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ctmirror.org/2010/05/22/democrats-malloy-and-wyman-vs-lamont-and-glassman/|title=Democrats: Malloy and Wyman vs. Lamont and Glassman|work=Connecticut Mirror|date=May 22, 2010 |accessdate=June 11, 2010}}</ref> On August 10, he lost the primary election to Malloy, receiving only 43% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/11/nyregion/11conn.html?_r=0|title=Lamont Loses Connecticut Primary for Governor|date=August 10, 2010|accessdate=February 8, 2013|work=[[The New York Times]]|first=Raymond|last=Hernandez}}</ref> Malloy would go on to defeat [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidate [[Thomas C. Foley]] in the general election.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-20022115-503544.html | work=CBS News | first=Brian | last=Montopoli | title=Tom Foley Concedes CT Governor Race | date=November 8, 2010}}</ref>\n\n====2018====\n{{main|2018 Connecticut gubernatorial election}}\n[[File:2018 Gubernatorial Election in Connecticut.svg|thumb|General election results by municipality. Shades of blue denote win for Lamont, red for Stefanowski.]]\nOn January 17, 2018, Lamont announced his candidacy to succeed Malloy, who was not seeking a third term.<ref>{{cite web|last=Colli|first=George|url=http://wtnh.com/2017/11/28/source-ned-lamont-thinking-seriously-about-run-for-governor/|title=Source: Ned Lamont \"thinking seriously\" about run for governor|work=[[WTNH]]|date=November 28, 2017|accessdate=November 28, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Lamont2018/> He received the party endorsement at the state convention, and chose former [[Connecticut Secretary of State]] [[Susan Bysiewicz]] as his running mate. While missing the 15% threshold, [[Bridgeport]] [[List of mayors of Bridgeport, Connecticut|mayor]] and former [[convict]] [[Joe Ganim]] had gathered enough signatures to appear on the Democratic primary ballot.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.courant.com/politics/elections/hc-pol-ganim-qualifies-primary-20180619-story.html|title=Joe Ganim And David Stemerman Qualify For Primaries For Governor |date=June 19, 2018|work=Hartford Courant|first=Neil|last=Vigdor|accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref> Despite the challenge, Lamont cruised to a landslide victory in the primary, winning by over 100,000 votes.<ref name=Lamont2018/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.courant.com/politics/elections/hc-pol-democratic-convention-nomination-governor-20180519-story.html |title=Second Chances: Democrats Endorse Ned Lamont For Governor, Joe Ganim Plans To Primary |last=Vigdor |first=Neil |last2=Altimari |first2=Daniela |website=Hartford Courant |last3=Keating |first3=Chris |last4=Gomez-Aceves |first4=Sandra|date=May 19, 2018|accessdate=May 19, 2018}}</ref> He then faced Republican [[Bob Stefanowski]] and independent [[Oz Griebel]] in the general election on November 6. Later that night, Greibel conceded the election, while Stefanowski conceded to Lamont early the next morning.<ref name=\"Courant2018Win\" />\n\n=== Tenure ===\nLamont was sworn in as the 89th governor of Connecticut on January 9, 2019, succeeding [[Dannel Malloy|Dan Malloy]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theday.com/article/20181107/NWS12/181109564|title=Stefanowski concedes race to Lamont: 'He won fair and square'|first1=Mark|last1=Pazniokas|first2=Keith M.|last2=Phaneuf|work=The Day|date=November 7, 2018|accessdate=November 8, 2018}}</ref> Some of his top priorities include: implementing [[Electronic toll collection|electronic tolls]] on state highways, taxing [[streaming media|online streaming services]], restoring the [[property tax]] [[tax credit|credit]], [[Cannabis in Connecticut|legalizing marijuana]] for recreational usage, increasing the [[Minimum wage in the United States|minimum wage]] to $15 per hour, instituting paid [[Parental leave|family]] and [[Sick leave|medical leave]], renegotiating contracts with [[Public-sector trade union|public-sector unions]], and legalizing [[sports betting]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.courant.com/politics/hc-pol-lamont-campaign-promises-20181116-story.html|title=Gov.-elect Ned Lamont made a lot of campaign promises. Which ones might happen?|first=Christopher|last=Keating|work=Hartford Courant|date=November 18, 2018|accessdate=November 21, 2018}}</ref> His proposal to implement electronic tolling on state highways has been viewed unfavorably by residents and has faced opposition from fellow Democrats in the [[Connecticut General Assembly|General Assembly]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctnewsjunkie.com/archives/entry/20190312_poll_finds_that_tolls_are_still_unpopular|title=Poll Finds That Tolls Are Still Unpopular|date=March 12, 2019|first=Christine|last=Stuart|work=CT News Junkie|accessdate=January 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://ctmirror.org/2019/11/13/lamont-gets-nowhere-on-tolls-with-senate-democrats|title=Lamont rebuffed on tolls by Senate Democrats|first1=Mark|last1=Pazniokas|first2=Keith M.|last2=Phaneuf|work=CT Mirror|date=November 13, 2019|accessdate=January 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe has also prioritized investments in rail infrastructure, proposing shorter travel times between cities by upgrading rail lines, as well as extending the [[Danbury Branch]] to [[New Milford station|New Milford]] and re-electrifying the line.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.courant.com/politics/hc-pol-ned-lamont-state-of-the-state-highlights-20190109-6nut5qb3cbd3xclsfizzepho5a-story.html|title=7 key lines from Ned Lamont's State of the State speech|work=Hartford Courant|first=Russell|last=Blair|date=January 9, 2019|accessdate=January 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newstimes.com/news/article/Gubernatorial-candidate-Ned-Lamont-talks-transit-542517.php|title=Gubernatorial candidate Ned Lamont talks transit at Danbury train station|first=Dirk|last=Perrefort|work=Danbury News-Times|date=June 30, 2010|accessdate=January 10, 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn February 2019, Lamont appointed former [[PepsiCo]] [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] [[Indra Nooyi]] co-director of the Connecticut Economic Resource Center (CERC), a [[public-private partnership]] with the Department of Economic and Community Development tasked with revamping the state's economic development strategy.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pazniokas |first1=Mark|date=February 1, 2019|title=A Wall Street exec volunteers, and Lamont readily accepts |url=https://ctmirror.org/2019/02/01/a-wall-street-exec-volunteers-and-lamont-readily-accepts/ |publisher=CT Mirror |accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Staff reporter |title=Connecticut Governor Names Indian American Executive Indra Nooyi to CERC Board of Directors to Improve Economic Strategy |url=https://www.indiawest.com/news/global_indian/connecticut-governor-names-indian-american-executive-indra-nooyi-to-cerc/article_0dc06bde-2bf9-11e9-8cea-77f61deeb5d7.html|date=February 11, 2019 |work=India West |accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref> A year later, CERC rebranded itself as AdvanceCT.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.advancect.org/about/|title=About Us|accessdate=March 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Lamont signed his first [[executive order]] which directs state office buildings and vehicle fleets to become more energy-efficient through an expanded \u201cLead By Example Sustainability Initiative.\" The initiative aims to reduce both the carbon footprint and cost of state government operations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wtnh.com/news/environment/lamont-wants-connecticut-to-reduce-greenhouse-gas-emissions-by-45-percent-by-2030/1950692784|title=Lamont wants Connecticut to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 45 percent by 2030|work=News 8|author=WTNH staff|date=April 24, 2019|accessdate=June 6, 2019}}</ref> On May 29, he signed a bill that raised the state minimum wage to $11 an hour that October and will eventually raise it to $15 an hour by 2023.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/445899-connecticut-governor-signs-bill-to-gradually-raise-minimum-wage-to-15|title=Connecticut governor signs bill to gradually raise minimum wage to $15 |work=The Hill|first=Morgan|last=Gstalter|date=May 29, 2019|accessdate=June 6, 2019}}</ref> On June 3, he signed three gun control bills including Ethan's Law, which requires safely storing firearms in households where children are present, bans [[ghost gun]]s, and bans storing unlocked guns in unattended vehicles.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.courant.com/politics/capitol-watch/hc-pol-three-gun-control-bills-ethans-law-lamont-20190603-4ww5nr5dyrevnbt6jcasb24kn4-story.html|title=Gov. Lamont signs three gun control bills, including Ethan's Law |work=Hartford Courant|first=Shannon|last=Larson|date=June 3, 2019|accessdate=June 6, 2019}}</ref> That same month, he signed a bill that banned [[gay panic defense]] in Connecticut.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/connecticut-lawmakers-move-ban-gay-213215029.html|title=Connecticut lawmakers move to ban 'gay panic defense'|work=Yahoo News|date=June 4, 2019|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.courant.com/politics/capitol-watch/hc-pol-gay-panic-defense-connecticut-20190604-hfyxsjurpzdblmislgnavosnsi-story.html|title=Bill banning gay panic defense gets final passage in the House|work=Hartford Courant|date=June 4, 2019|accessdate=March 4, 2020|last=Altimari|first=Daniela}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://legiscan.com/CT/bill/SB00058/2019|title=CT SB00058|work=LegiScan|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the aftermath of the [[2019 Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress crash]], which resulted in seven deaths and six injuries, Lamont was joined with Senator [[Richard Blumenthal]] in offering condolences to the families affected and ensuring them that the [[NTSB]] would launch a thorough investigation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/plane-crash-at-bradley-airport-boeing-b-17-flying-fortress-crashes-connecticut-today-live-updates/|title=World War II-era bomber plane crashes at Bradley Airport in Connecticut; fatalities confirmed |work=CBS News|first=Brian|last=Pascus|date=October 2, 2019|accessdate=November 15, 2019}}</ref> Lamont later met with the first responders to thank them for their service.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcconnecticut.com/news/local/Governor-Thanks-B17-Survivor-and-Responding-Air-National-Guard-Members-564126821.html|title=Governor Thanks B17 Survivor and Responding Air National Guard Members|work=NBC Connecticut|first=Caitlin|last=Burchill|date=October 30, 2019|accessdate=November 15, 2019}}</ref>  \n\n'''Approval ratings'''\n\nSince being elected governor, Connecticut residents have viewed Lamont unfavorably. [[Morning Consult]] has listed him among the top ten least popular governors every quarter since his election. In a survey conducted in the last quarter of 2019, he was ranked the fourth most unpopular governor in the United States, with a 51% disapproval rating and a 32% approval rating.<ref name=MorningConsult>{{cite web|url=https://morningconsult.com/governor-rankings/|title=Morning Consult's Governor Approval Ratings|work=[[Morning Consult]]|date=April 2019|accessdate=May 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn September 10, 1983,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/07/17/style/ann-huntress-to-wed-em-lamont-jr.html|title=Ann Huntress to Wed E.M. Lamont Jr.|date=July 17, 1983|work=The New York Times|accessdate=October 22, 2018}}</ref> Lamont married [[Ann Lamont|Ann Huntress]], a [[venture capital]]ist and managing partner at [[Oak Investment Partners]].<ref name=\"moffly\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/16/nyregion/16wife.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|title=Not-So-Hidden Asset, His Wife, Is Force in Lamont's Senate Bid|date=October 16, 2006|accessdate=February 8, 2013|first=Alison Leigh|last=Cowan|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> They have three children: Emily, Lindsay, and Teddy.<ref name=\"moffly\"/> He and his family live in [[Greenwich, Connecticut|Greenwich]] and have a [[vacation home]] in [[North Haven, Maine]].<ref name=\"Kershaw\"/>\n\nThe [[Lamont Gallery]] on the campus of [[Phillips Exeter Academy]] and the [[Lamont Library]] at [[Harvard University]] are both named in honor of his family.<ref name=\"Kershaw\"/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notes}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n{{Wikinews category}}\n* [https://portal.ct.gov/Office-of-the-Governor Governor Ned Lamont] official government website\n* {{Ballotpedia}}\n* {{C-SPAN|nedlamont02}}\n* {{imdb name|2331703}}\n* [http://www.ontheissues.org/Senate/Ned_Lamont.htm Ned Lamont] at [[On the Issues]]\n* {{CongLinks|votesmart=68381}}\n* {{worldcat id|lccn-no2012139378|Ned Lamont}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Joe Lieberman]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[United States Senator|U.S. Senator]] from [[Connecticut]]<br>([[Classes of United States Senators|Class 1]])|years=[[United States Senate election in Connecticut, 2006|2006]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Chris Murphy]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dannel Malloy|Dan Malloy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[List of governors of Connecticut|Governor of Connecticut]]|years=[[2018 Connecticut gubernatorial election|2018]]}}\n{{s-inc|recent}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dannel Malloy|Dan Malloy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of governors of Connecticut|Governor of Connecticut]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Mike Pence]]|as=[[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]]}}\n{{s-ttl|rows=2|title=[[United States order of precedence|Order of Precedence of the United States]]|years=Within Connecticut}}\n{{s-aft|after=Mayor of city<br>in which event is held}}\n|-\n{{s-aft|after=Otherwise {{Incumbent U.S. House Speaker}}<br>{{nowrap|{{small|''as [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives]]''}}}}}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Brian Kemp]]|as=[[Governor of Georgia]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States order of precedence|Order of Precedence of the United States]]|years=Outside Connecticut}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Charlie Baker]]|as=[[Governor of Massachusetts]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Governors of Connecticut}}\n{{Current U.S. Governors}}\n{{Current Connecticut statewide political officials}}\n{{portal bar|Biography|Connecticut|Politics}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lamont, Ned}}\n[[Category:Ned Lamont|*]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century American newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American anti\u2013Iraq War activists]]\n[[Category:Brookings Institution]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Greenwich, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Central Connecticut State University faculty]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Editors of Vermont newspapers]]\n[[Category:Governors of Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Harvard College alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Institute of Politics]]\n[[Category:Lamont family|n]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Laurel Hollow, New York]]\n[[Category:People from Ludlow, Vermont]]\n[[Category:People from North Haven, Maine]]\n[[Category:Phillips Exeter Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Yale School of Management alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{good article}}\n{{short description|89th Governor of Connecticut}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Ned Lamont\n|image       = Governor Ned Lamont of Connecticut, official portrait.jpg\n|order       = 89th [[List of governors of Connecticut|Governor of Connecticut]]\n|lieutenant  = [[Susan Bysiewicz]]\n|term_start  = January 9, 2019\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[Dannel Malloy|Dan Malloy]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_name  = Edward Miner Lamont Jr.\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1954|1|3}}\n|birth_place = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse      = {{marriage|[[Ann Lamont|Ann Huntress]]|September 10, 1983}}\n|children    = 3\n|residence   = [[Connecticut Governor's Residence|Governor's Mansion]] \n|education   = [[Harvard University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Yale University]] ([[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])\n|website     = {{url|portal.ct.gov/Office-of-the-Governor|Government website}}\n}}\n'''Edward Miner Lamont Jr.''' (born January 3, 1954) is an American businessman and politician serving as the [[List of governors of Connecticut|89th governor of Connecticut]] since January 9, 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://greenwich.dailyvoice.com/neighbors/happy-birthday-to-greenwichs-ned-lamont-jr/552594/|title=Happy Birthday to Greenwich's Ned Lamont Jr.|work=Greenwich Daily Voice|date=January 3, 2014|accessdate=August 15, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Courant2018Win\">{{cite news|last1=Vigdor|first1=Neil|last2=Kovner|first2=Josh|last3=Lender|first3=Jon|last4=Ormseth|first4=Matthew|last5=Megan|first5=Kathleen|last6=Rondinone|first6=Nicholas|title=Bob Stefanowski Concedes Governor's Race After Cities Push Ned Lamont To Victory|url=https://www.courant.com/politics/elections/hc-election-governor-connecticut-lamont-stefanowski-20181101-story.html|work=[[Hartford Courant]]|date=November 7, 2018|accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref> A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], he served as a [[Greenwich, Connecticut|Greenwich]] selectman from 1987 to 1989. He ran for the [[U.S. Senate]] in [[2006 United States Senate election in Connecticut|2006]], defeating incumbent Senator [[Joe Lieberman]] in the state Democratic primary election, but was later defeated in the general election by Lieberman, who then ran as a [[Connecticut for Lieberman|third-party]] candidate.<ref name=Lamont2018/>\n\nLamont then ran for governor in [[2010 Connecticut gubernatorial election|2010]], but was defeated in the Democratic primary by former [[Stamford, Connecticut|Stamford]] [[Mayor of Stamford, Connecticut|mayor]] [[Dannel Malloy|Dan Malloy]], who went on to win the general election. Lamont ran again in [[2018 Connecticut gubernatorial election|2018]], winning the party nomination and defeating Republican [[Bob Stefanowski]] in the general election.<ref name=Lamont2018>{{cite web|last=Blair|first=Russell|url=http://www.courant.com/politics/hc-pol-ned-lamont-governors-race-20180117-story.html|title=Ned Lamont Jumps Into Connecticut Governor's Race|work=[[Hartford Courant]]|date=January 17, 2018|accessdate=January 17, 2018}}</ref> He uses his nickname '''Ned''' in his official capacity as governor, as he has done throughout his public life.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.courant.com/politics/capitol-watch/hc-pol-edward-ned-lamont-20181212-story.html|title=Ned or Edward? Lamont keeps it informal as governor|first=Daniela|last=Altimari|date=December 12, 2018|accessdate=June 10, 2019|work=Hartford Courant}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nLamont was born on January 3, 1954, in [[Washington, D.C.]], to Camille Helene (n\u00e9e Buzby) and Edward Miner Lamont. His mother was born in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]] to parents from the U.S. mainland, and later worked as a staffer for Senator [[Estes Kefauver]].<ref name=\"Legacy\">{{cite news|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/nytimes/obituary.aspx?pid=173841282 |title=Camille Lamont Obituary|newspaper=The New York Times|date=January 14, 2015|accessdate=October 9, 2016}}</ref> His father, an economist, worked on the [[Marshall Plan]] and then served in the [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development|Department of Housing and Urban Development]] during the [[Presidency of Richard Nixon|Nixon administration]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenation.com/article/fight-partys-soul|title=A Fight for the Party's Soul|first=John|last=Nichols|work=[[The Nation]]|date=July 27, 2006|accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> He is the great-grandson of former [[J. P. Morgan & Co.]] chair [[Thomas W. Lamont]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wargs.com/other/lamont.html|title=Ancestry of Ned Lamont|first=William Addams|last=Reitwiesner|accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the40yearplan.com/article_012406.php|work=The 40-Year Plan|title=Ned Lamont (interview)|first=Ken|last=Krayeske|date=January 24, 2006|accessdate=August 5, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070225081606/http://www.the40yearplan.com/article_012406.php|archivedate=February 25, 2007}}</ref> and a grand-nephew of former [[American Civil Liberties Union]] director [[Corliss Lamont]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.corliss-lamont.org/|title=The Life of Corliss Lamont|date=May 27, 2018|accessdate=August 15, 2018|publisher=Half-Moon Foundation, Inc.}}</ref> He is a distant descendant of colonial diarist [[Thomas Minor]], from whom he gets his middle name.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/15/opinion/nyregionopinions/15CT_Sleeper.html|title=The American Lamonts|work=The New York Times|first=Jim|last=Sleeper|accessdate=February 27, 2019|date=October 15, 2006}}</ref>{{efn|The spelling of Minor's [[surname]] has historically varied between ''Minor'' and ''Miner''.<ref name=Curious>Miner, John A. and Miner, Robert F. \"The Curious Pedigree of Lt. Thomas Minor\". ''New England Historical and Genealogical Register''. New England Historic Genealogical Society. July 1984, pg 182-185. Accessed 14 July 2007.</ref>\n}}\n\nLamont's family moved to [[Laurel Hollow, New York|Laurel Hollow]] on [[Long Island]] when he was seven years old.{{efn|Some media outlets erroneously report Lamont's childhood home as [[Syosset, New York]] due to its shared [[ZIP Code]] (11791) with Laurel Hollow.<ref name=\"Kershaw\"/><ref name=\"Legacy\"/>}} The eldest of three children, he and his sisters attended [[East Woods School]].<ref name=\"Legacy\"/><ref name=\"Kershaw\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/01/nyregion/01lamont.html|title=A Son of Privilege Takes His Baby Steps on the Political Proving Ground|work=The New York Times|first1=Sarah|last1=Kershaw|first2=Alison Leigh|last2=Cowan|date=November 1, 2006|accessdate=November 9, 2018}}</ref> He later attended [[Phillips Exeter Academy]], and served as president of the student newspaper, ''[[The Exonian]]''. After graduating from Phillips Exeter in 1972, he earned a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[sociology]] from [[Harvard College]] in 1976 and a [[Master of Business Administration]] from the [[Yale School of Management]] in 1980.<ref name=\"Kershaw\"/><ref name=\"CT mirror\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ctmirror.org/node/6058/candidate|title=Ned Lamont: Democrat candidate for Governor|work=[[The Connecticut Mirror]]|accessdate=August 5, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100704084345/http://www.ctmirror.org/node/6058/candidate|archivedate=July 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nIn 1977, Lamont became editor for the ''[[Black River Tribune]]'', a small weekly newspaper in [[Ludlow (village), Vermont|Ludlow, Vermont]]. During his time there, he worked alongside journalists [[Jane Mayer]] and [[Alex Beam]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.courant.com/2010-08-02/news/hc-primary-gov-ned-lamont-0803-20100802_1_stamford-mayor-dannel-malloy-bitter-race-republicans-and-democrats|title=Unknown No Longer, Lamont Runs For Governor|first=Christopher|last=Keating|newspaper=Hartford Courant|date=August 2, 2010|accessdate=August 28, 2018}}</ref> After graduating from Yale, he entered the cable television industry, managing the startup operation in [[Fairfield County, Connecticut]] for [[Cablevision]].<ref name=\"CT mirror\"/> In 1984, he founded Campus Televideo, a company that provides cable and satellite services to college campuses across the United States.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hartfordbusiness.com/article/20180720/NEWHAVENBIZ/180729989/lamont-in-the-lions-den|title=Lamont in the lion's den|work=New Haven Biz|date=July 20, 2018|first=Michael C.|last=Bingham|accessdate=August 29, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Keating>{{cite news|url=http://www.courant.com/politics/capitol-watch/hc-pol-lamont-sold-cable-tv-company-20180119-story.html|title=After Selling Cable Company, Ned Lamont is 'All In'|first=Christopher|last=Keating|newspaper=Hartford Courant|date=January 19, 2018|accessdate=August 29, 2018}}</ref> He later chaired Lamont Digital Systems, a telecommunications firm that invests in [[new media]] startups.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/profiles/companies/9889540Z:US-lamont-digital-systems-inc|title=Lamont Digital Systems Inc|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=August 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctpost.com/politics/article/Ned-Lamont-s-cable-business-had-an-MTV-13111577.php|title=Ned Lamont's cable business launched with tip from MTV|first=Dan|last=Haar|newspaper=Connecticut Post|date=July 28, 2018|accessdate=August 28, 2018}}</ref> Campus Televideo was its largest division before [[Austin, Texas]]-based firm Apogee acquired it on September 3, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marketwired.com/press-release/apogee-acquires-campus-televideo-becomes-higher-educations-largest-resnet-video-solutions-2052678.htm|title=Apogee Acquires Campus Televideo -- Becomes Higher Education's Largest ResNet and Video Solutions Provider|date=September 3, 2015|work=Market Wired}}</ref><ref name=Keating/>\n\nLamont has served on the [[board of trustees]] for the [[Conservation Services Group]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nedlamont.com/about|title=About Ned|accessdate=November 29, 2018|publisher=Ned for CT}}</ref> [[Mercy Corps]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mercycorps.org/articles/iraq/ned-lamont-calls-out-mercy-corps-work-huffington-post|title=Ned Lamont calls out Mercy Corps' work on The Huffington Post|work=Mercy Corps|first=Joy|last=Portella|date=June 30, 2009|accessdate=August 29, 2018}}</ref> the [[Norman Rockwell Museum]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrm.org/2011/09/norman-rockwell-museum-announces-new-board-members/|title=Norman Rockwell Museum Announces New Board Members|work=[[Norman Rockwell Museum]]|date=September 9, 2011|accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> the [[YMCA]], and the [[Young Presidents' Organization]].<ref name=\"moffly\">{{cite web|url=https://ilovefc.com/2006/04/19/ned-lamont-makes-a-run-for-the-us-senate/|title=Ned Lamont Makes a Run for the US Senate|date=April 19, 2006|publisher=Moffly Media|website=ilovefc.com|accessdate=August 15, 2018}}</ref> He has also served on the advisory boards of the [[Yale School of Management]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://som.yale.edu/community/school-leadership-boards/boards-councils/yale-som-board-of-advisors|title=Yale SOM Board of Advisors|work=Yale School of Management|publisher=Yale University|accessdate=August 15, 2018}}</ref> and the [[Brookings Institution]].<ref name=\"moffly\"/>\n\n==Early political career==\n{{see also|Electoral history of Ned Lamont}}\nLamont was first elected in 1987 as a [[selectman]] in [[Greenwich, Connecticut]], where he served for one term. He ran for [[Connecticut Senate|state senate]] in 1990, where he faced Republican William Nickerson and incumbent senator Emil \"Bennie\" Benvenuto (who had switched his party affiliation from Republican to [[A Connecticut Party]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.courant.com/politics/capitol-watch/hc-greenwich-mourns-death-of-former-sen-bennie-benvenuto-ran-against-ned-lamont-and-bill-nickerson-in-1990-senate-race-20111012-story.html|title=Greenwich Mourns Death Of Former Sen. Bennie Benvenuto; Ran Against Ned Lamont And Bill Nickerson In Three-Way 1990 State Senate Race|work=Hartford Courant|first=Christopher|last=Keating|date=October 12, 2011|accessdate=January 2, 2019}}</ref> Nickerson won the three-way race with Lamont finishing in third place.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=697193|publisher=Our Campaigns|title=CT State Senate 36|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref> Lamont later served for three terms on the Greenwich town finance board and chaired the State Investment Advisory Council, which oversees state pension fund investments. During his term as chair, the state saw its unfunded liabilities reduced and pension fund performance improved.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myleftnutmeg.com/showDiary.do?diaryId=237|work=MyLeftNutmeg|title=Lamont Grants MyLeftNutmeg First Blogger Interview|date=January 13, 2006|accessdate=August 3, 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060613193545/http://www.myleftnutmeg.com/showDiary.do?diaryId=237|archivedate=June 13, 2006}}</ref>\n\n===2006 U.S. Senate election===\n{{main|2006 United States Senate election in Connecticut}}\n[[File:United States Senate election results in Connecticut by municipality, 2006.svg|thumb|General election results by municipality. Shades of blue denote win for Lamont, yellow for Lieberman.]]\n[[File:NedLamont2006.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Lamont in 2006.]]\n[[File:Ned Lamont YearlyKos 2007 (1000450845).jpg|thumb|220px|Lamont attending the [[Netroots Nation#2007|2007 YearlyKos]] conference at the [[McCormick Place]] in [[Chicago]].]]\nOn March 13, 2006, Lamont announced his campaign for the U.S. Senate against incumbent [[Joe Lieberman]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yaledailynews.com/blog/2006/04/06/lamont-courts-local-voters/|title=Lamont courts local voters|first=Melina|last=Cordero|date=April 6, 2006|accessdate=February 8, 2013|work=[[Yale Daily News]]}}</ref>\n\nOn July 6, Lamont faced off against Lieberman in a televised debate that covered issues such as the [[Iraq War]], energy policy, and [[immigration]]. During the debate, Lieberman argued he was being subjected to a [[Litmus test (politics)|litmus test]] on the war, insisted he was a \"bread-and-butter Democrat,\" and on many occasions asked, \"who is Ned Lamont?\" Lieberman then asked Lamont if he would release his [[income tax]] returns, which he did afterwards.<ref name=NBCFaceOff>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbc30.com/politics/9481028/detail.html|title=Lieberman, Lamont Face Off In NBC 30 Debate|work=[[WVIT]]|date=July 6, 2006|accessdate=August 5, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071225190159/http://www.nbc30.com/politics/9481028/detail.html|archivedate=December 25, 2007}}</ref>\n\nLamont focused on Lieberman's supportive relationship with Republicans, telling him \"if you won't challenge [[George W. Bush|President Bush]] and his failed agenda, I will.\" He criticized Lieberman's vote for the [[Energy Policy Act of 2005]], which he dubbed the \"Bush-[[Dick Cheney|Cheney]]-Lieberman energy bill.\" In response to the assertion that he supported Republican policies, Lieberman stated he had voted with [[Senate Democratic Caucus|Senate Democrats]] 90% of the time. Lamont argued the three-term incumbent lacked the courage to challenge the [[Presidency of George W. Bush|Bush administration]] on the Iraq War.<ref name=\"NBCFaceOff\"/> He also criticized Lieberman for supporting federal intervention in the [[Terri Schiavo case]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://inthesetimes.com/article/2549/why_ned_lamont_is_a_democrat|title=Why Ned Lamont is a Democrat|date=March 21, 2006|last=Seder|first=Sam|accessdate=August 15, 2018|work=In These Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.truthdig.com/articles/ned-lamont-the-truthdig-interview/|title=Ned Lamont: The Truthdig Interview|last=Golson|first=Blair|date=April 26, 2006|accessdate=August 15, 2018|work=TruthDig}}</ref>\n\nOn July 30, ''[[The New York Times]]'' editorial board endorsed Lamont.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/30/opinion/30sun1.html?_r=1&oref=slogin|title=A Senate Race in Connecticut|date=July 30, 2006|accessdate=August 15, 2018|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> That same day, ''[[The Sunday Times (UK)|The Sunday Times]]'' reported former President [[Bill Clinton]] warned Lieberman not to run as an independent if he lost the primary to Lamont.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/the-anti-war-tycoon-splits-democrats-k0fq0w57gfl|work=[[The Sunday Times (UK)|The Sunday Times]]|title=The anti-war tycoon splits Democrats|first=Tony|last=Allen-Mills|date=July 30, 2006|accessdate=August 3, 2006}}</ref> Pledging to refuse money from [[lobbyist]]s during the election, Lamont funded most of his own campaign, with donations exceeding $12.7 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/10/21/AR2006102101016.html|title=Lamont Gives $2M to Flagging Campaign|first=Andrew|last=Miga|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=October 21, 2006|accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://lamontblog.blogspot.com/2006/04/4000-donors-in-first-quarter.html|title=4,000 Donors in First Quarter|date=April 3, 2006|accessdate=August 5, 2013|work=LamontBlog|first=Ned|last=Lamont}}</ref>\n\nLamont won the primary with 52% of the vote<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/files/elections/2006/by_state/CT_Page_0808.html?SITE=CTHARELN&SECTION=POLITICS|title=Connecticut primary results|newspaper=Hartford Courant|date=August 10, 2006|accessdate=August 5, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130325075023/http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/files/elections/2006/by_state/CT_Page_0808.html?SITE=CTHARELN&SECTION=POLITICS|archivedate=March 25, 2013}}</ref> (this was the only [[2006 United States Senate elections|Senate race in 2006]] where an incumbent lost re-nomination). In his concession speech, Lieberman announced he was standing by his earlier statements that he would run as an independent if he lost the Democratic primary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/14228351/#.URRQYGdU5co|title=Lieberman concedes; Lamont wins primary|date=August 9, 2006|accessdate=February 8, 2013|work=[[NBC News]]}}</ref> Running under the banner of [[Connecticut for Lieberman]], Lieberman won the general election with nearly 50% of the vote (exit polls showed Lieberman won 33% of Democrats, 54% of independents, and 70% of Republicans).<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/ELECTION/2006/pages/results/states/CT/S/01/epolls.0.html|work=[[CNN]]|title=America Votes 2006: Exit Polls|accessdate=August 5, 2013}}</ref> The [[Sundance TV|Sundance Channel]] documentary film ''[[Blog Wars]]'' chronicled the influence [[political blogging]] had on the election.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.powerlineblog.com/archives/2006/12/016037.php|first=John|last=Hinderaker|date=December 26, 2006|accessdate=March 4, 2019|title=Blog Wars|work=Power Line}}</ref>\n\nWhile some [[Research 2000]] polls commissioned by the [[Daily Kos]] in 2007 and 2008 found he would win a Senate rematch with Lieberman by growing margins,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailykos.com/story/2008/04/07/491459/-CT-Sen-Lieberman-s-popularity-continues-to-slide|work=[[Daily Kos]]|title=CT-Sen: Lieberman's popularity continues to slide|date=April 7, 2008|accessdate=August 5, 2013|first=Markos|last=Moulitsas}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/campaigns/43974-poll-lieberman-would-lose-to-lamont|title=Poll: Lieberman Would Lose to Lamont|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|first=Walter|last=Alarkon|date=July 6, 2008|accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> Lamont stated he was not considering another campaign for Senate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctmirror.org/story/2010/12/07/lamont-not-looking-rematch-lieberman-2012|title=Lamont not looking for a rematch with Lieberman in 2012|work=Connecticut Mirror|first=Mark|last=Pazniokas|date=December 8, 2010|accessdate=August 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2008 presidential campaign activity===\nLamont initially supported [[Chris Dodd]]'s [[Chris Dodd 2008 presidential campaign|presidential campaign]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/ari-melber/ned-lamont-backs-habeas-c_b_42069.html|title=Ned Lamont Backs Habeas Corpus- and Chris Dodd|first=Ari|last=Melber|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=February 25, 2007|accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071225193654/http://www.thepolitic.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=77&Itemid=38|title=\"Ned Who\" No More: An interview with Ned Lamont|first=Christopher|last=Gombeski|date=November 10, 2007|accessdate=August 15, 2008|work=The Politic}}</ref> After Dodd dropped out of the race, Lamont became a state co-chair for [[Barack Obama]]'s [[Barack Obama 2008 presidential campaign|presidential campaign]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/ned-lamont/why-im-supporting-barack_b_80986.html|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|first=Ned|last=Lamont|title=Why I'm Supporting Barack Obama|date=March 28, 2008|accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> Obama's victory in the [[2008 Connecticut Democratic primary|Connecticut Democratic primary]] was credited to Lamont's ability to turn out the voter base he had built during his Senate campaign.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/06/us/politics/06region.html?ref=nyregion|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=Obama Takes Connecticut, Helped by Lamont Voters|first=David W.|last=Chen|date=February 6, 2008|accessdate=May 20, 2010}}</ref> In March 2008, he was elected as a state delegate to the [[2008 Democratic National Convention]], his support pledged to Obama.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thegreenpapers.com/P08/CT-D.phtml|work=The Green Papers|title=Connecticut Democratic Delegation 2008|date=February 5, 2008|accessdate=July 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Academic career==\n[[File:Ned Lamont and Merle Harris (2557042728) (cropped).jpg|thumb|220px|Lamont speaking with former CCSU president Merle Harris in June 2008.]]\nBefore the 2006 election, Lamont had volunteered at [[Warren Harding High School]] in [[Bridgeport, Connecticut|Bridgeport]], where he focused on teaching entrepreneurship and coordinating internships with local businesses.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctpost.com/news/article/Testing-Lamont-s-ties-to-Harding-High-12991863.php|title=Fact checking Lamont's ties to Harding High||first=Brian|last=Lockhart|date=June 13, 2018|work=Connecticut Post|accessdate=October 29, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"CONEG\">{{cite web|url=https://www.coneg.org/governor/ned-lamont/|title=Edward Miner \u201cNed\u201d Lamont, Jr., Connecticut Governor|work=Coalition of Northeastern Governors|accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref>  After the election, he served as a teaching [[fellow]] at the [[Harvard Institute of Politics]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iop.harvard.edu/former-fellows/L|title=Former Fellows-The Institute of Politics|work=[[Harvard Institute of Politics]]|accessdate=February 8, 2013|publisher=[[Harvard University]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022154552/http://www.iop.harvard.edu/former-fellows/L|archivedate=October 22, 2012}}</ref> and the Yale School of Management. He then became an adjunct faculty member and chair of the Arts and Sciences Public Policy Committee at [[Central Connecticut State University]] (CCSU), where he was named Distinguished Professor of Political Science and Philosophy.<ref name=\"CONEG\"/> During his time at CCSU, he was a [[lecturer]] in multiple classes and founded a business startup competition.<ref name=\"CONEG\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctpost.com/politics/article/Ned-Lamont-s-eight-year-break-from-politics-13321174.php|title=Ned Lamont\u2019s eight-year break from politics|date=October 21, 2018|first=Kaitlyn|last=Krasselt|work=CT Post|accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref> In 2019, he delivered the [[commencement speech]] for CCSU, his first as governor.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.apnews.com/a358fc64e1924613bd18ac8c9029d11e|title=Gov. Ned Lamont to deliver commencement remarks at CCSU|date=May 12, 2019|work=Associated Press|accessdate=June 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Governor of Connecticut (2019\u2013present)==\n===Elections===\n====2010====\n{{main|2010 Connecticut gubernatorial election}}\nOn February 16, 2010, Lamont announced his candidacy for the [[2010 Connecticut gubernatorial election|2010 gubernatorial election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ctmirror.org/2010/02/16/lamont-announces-governor-pitching-himself-outsider/|title=Lamont announces for governor, pitching himself as an outsider|first=Mark|last=Pazniokas|work=[[Connecticut Mirror]]|date=February 16, 2010|accessdate=August 29, 2010}}</ref> Former [[Stamford, Connecticut|Stamford]] mayor [[Dannel Malloy|Dan Malloy]] defeated him at the state Democratic convention on May 22, receiving 1,232 votes (68%) to Lamont's 582 votes (32%). Since he won more than 15% of the vote, Lamont was eligible to appear on the primary election ballot.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ctmirror.org/2010/05/22/democrats-malloy-and-wyman-vs-lamont-and-glassman/|title=Democrats: Malloy and Wyman vs. Lamont and Glassman|work=Connecticut Mirror|date=May 22, 2010 |accessdate=June 11, 2010}}</ref> On August 10, he lost the primary election to Malloy, receiving only 43% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/11/nyregion/11conn.html?_r=0|title=Lamont Loses Connecticut Primary for Governor|date=August 10, 2010|accessdate=February 8, 2013|work=[[The New York Times]]|first=Raymond|last=Hernandez}}</ref> Malloy would go on to defeat [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidate [[Thomas C. Foley]] in the general election.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-20022115-503544.html | work=CBS News | first=Brian | last=Montopoli | title=Tom Foley Concedes CT Governor Race | date=November 8, 2010}}</ref>\n\n====2018====\n{{main|2018 Connecticut gubernatorial election}}\n[[File:2018 Gubernatorial Election in Connecticut.svg|thumb|General election results by municipality. Shades of blue denote win for Lamont, red for Stefanowski.]]\nOn January 17, 2018, Lamont announced his candidacy to succeed Malloy, who was not seeking a third term.<ref>{{cite web|last=Colli|first=George|url=http://wtnh.com/2017/11/28/source-ned-lamont-thinking-seriously-about-run-for-governor/|title=Source: Ned Lamont \"thinking seriously\" about run for governor|work=[[WTNH]]|date=November 28, 2017|accessdate=November 28, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Lamont2018/> He received the party endorsement at the state convention, and chose former [[Connecticut Secretary of State]] [[Susan Bysiewicz]] as his running mate. While missing the 15% threshold, [[Bridgeport]] [[List of mayors of Bridgeport, Connecticut|mayor]] and former [[convict]] [[Joe Ganim]] had gathered enough signatures to appear on the Democratic primary ballot.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.courant.com/politics/elections/hc-pol-ganim-qualifies-primary-20180619-story.html|title=Joe Ganim And David Stemerman Qualify For Primaries For Governor |date=June 19, 2018|work=Hartford Courant|first=Neil|last=Vigdor|accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref> Despite the challenge, Lamont cruised to a landslide victory in the primary, winning by over 100,000 votes.<ref name=Lamont2018/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.courant.com/politics/elections/hc-pol-democratic-convention-nomination-governor-20180519-story.html |title=Second Chances: Democrats Endorse Ned Lamont For Governor, Joe Ganim Plans To Primary |last=Vigdor |first=Neil |last2=Altimari |first2=Daniela |website=Hartford Courant |last3=Keating |first3=Chris |last4=Gomez-Aceves |first4=Sandra|date=May 19, 2018|accessdate=May 19, 2018}}</ref> He then faced Republican [[Bob Stefanowski]] and independent [[Oz Griebel]] in the general election on November 6. Later that night, Greibel conceded the election, while Stefanowski conceded to Lamont early the next morning.<ref name=\"Courant2018Win\" />\n\n=== Tenure ===\nLamont was sworn in as the 89th governor of Connecticut on January 9, 2019, succeeding [[Dannel Malloy|Dan Malloy]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theday.com/article/20181107/NWS12/181109564|title=Stefanowski concedes race to Lamont: 'He won fair and square'|first1=Mark|last1=Pazniokas|first2=Keith M.|last2=Phaneuf|work=The Day|date=November 7, 2018|accessdate=November 8, 2018}}</ref> Some of his top priorities include: implementing [[Electronic toll collection|electronic tolls]] on state highways, taxing [[streaming media|online streaming services]], restoring the [[property tax]] [[tax credit|credit]], [[Cannabis in Connecticut|legalizing marijuana]] for recreational usage, increasing the [[Minimum wage in the United States|minimum wage]] to $15 per hour, instituting paid [[Parental leave|family]] and [[Sick leave|medical leave]], renegotiating contracts with [[Public-sector trade union|public-sector unions]], and legalizing [[sports betting]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.courant.com/politics/hc-pol-lamont-campaign-promises-20181116-story.html|title=Gov.-elect Ned Lamont made a lot of campaign promises. Which ones might happen?|first=Christopher|last=Keating|work=Hartford Courant|date=November 18, 2018|accessdate=November 21, 2018}}</ref> His proposal to implement electronic tolling on state highways has been viewed unfavorably by residents and has faced opposition from fellow Democrats in the [[Connecticut General Assembly|General Assembly]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctnewsjunkie.com/archives/entry/20190312_poll_finds_that_tolls_are_still_unpopular|title=Poll Finds That Tolls Are Still Unpopular|date=March 12, 2019|first=Christine|last=Stuart|work=CT News Junkie|accessdate=January 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://ctmirror.org/2019/11/13/lamont-gets-nowhere-on-tolls-with-senate-democrats|title=Lamont rebuffed on tolls by Senate Democrats|first1=Mark|last1=Pazniokas|first2=Keith M.|last2=Phaneuf|work=CT Mirror|date=November 13, 2019|accessdate=January 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe has also prioritized investments in rail infrastructure, proposing shorter travel times between cities by upgrading rail lines, as well as extending the [[Danbury Branch]] to [[New Milford station|New Milford]] and re-electrifying the line.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.courant.com/politics/hc-pol-ned-lamont-state-of-the-state-highlights-20190109-6nut5qb3cbd3xclsfizzepho5a-story.html|title=7 key lines from Ned Lamont's State of the State speech|work=Hartford Courant|first=Russell|last=Blair|date=January 9, 2019|accessdate=January 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newstimes.com/news/article/Gubernatorial-candidate-Ned-Lamont-talks-transit-542517.php|title=Gubernatorial candidate Ned Lamont talks transit at Danbury train station|first=Dirk|last=Perrefort|work=Danbury News-Times|date=June 30, 2010|accessdate=January 10, 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn February 2019, Lamont appointed former [[PepsiCo]] [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] [[Indra Nooyi]] co-director of the Connecticut Economic Resource Center (CERC), a [[public-private partnership]] with the Department of Economic and Community Development tasked with revamping the state's economic development strategy.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pazniokas |first1=Mark|date=February 1, 2019|title=A Wall Street exec volunteers, and Lamont readily accepts |url=https://ctmirror.org/2019/02/01/a-wall-street-exec-volunteers-and-lamont-readily-accepts/ |publisher=CT Mirror |accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Staff reporter |title=Connecticut Governor Names Indian American Executive Indra Nooyi to CERC Board of Directors to Improve Economic Strategy |url=https://www.indiawest.com/news/global_indian/connecticut-governor-names-indian-american-executive-indra-nooyi-to-cerc/article_0dc06bde-2bf9-11e9-8cea-77f61deeb5d7.html|date=February 11, 2019 |work=India West |accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref> A year later, CERC rebranded itself as AdvanceCT.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.advancect.org/about/|title=About Us|accessdate=March 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Lamont signed his first [[executive order]] which directs state office buildings and vehicle fleets to become more energy-efficient through an expanded \u201cLead By Example Sustainability Initiative.\" The initiative aims to reduce both the carbon footprint and cost of state government operations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wtnh.com/news/environment/lamont-wants-connecticut-to-reduce-greenhouse-gas-emissions-by-45-percent-by-2030/1950692784|title=Lamont wants Connecticut to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 45 percent by 2030|work=News 8|author=WTNH staff|date=April 24, 2019|accessdate=June 6, 2019}}</ref> On May 29, he signed a bill that raised the state minimum wage to $11 an hour that October and will eventually raise it to $15 an hour by 2023.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/445899-connecticut-governor-signs-bill-to-gradually-raise-minimum-wage-to-15|title=Connecticut governor signs bill to gradually raise minimum wage to $15 |work=The Hill|first=Morgan|last=Gstalter|date=May 29, 2019|accessdate=June 6, 2019}}</ref> On June 3, he signed three gun control bills including Ethan's Law, which requires safely storing firearms in households where children are present, bans [[ghost gun]]s, and bans storing unlocked guns in unattended vehicles.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.courant.com/politics/capitol-watch/hc-pol-three-gun-control-bills-ethans-law-lamont-20190603-4ww5nr5dyrevnbt6jcasb24kn4-story.html|title=Gov. Lamont signs three gun control bills, including Ethan's Law |work=Hartford Courant|first=Shannon|last=Larson|date=June 3, 2019|accessdate=June 6, 2019}}</ref> That same month, he signed a bill that banned [[gay panic defense]] in Connecticut.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/connecticut-lawmakers-move-ban-gay-213215029.html|title=Connecticut lawmakers move to ban 'gay panic defense'|work=Yahoo News|date=June 4, 2019|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.courant.com/politics/capitol-watch/hc-pol-gay-panic-defense-connecticut-20190604-hfyxsjurpzdblmislgnavosnsi-story.html|title=Bill banning gay panic defense gets final passage in the House|work=Hartford Courant|date=June 4, 2019|accessdate=March 4, 2020|last=Altimari|first=Daniela}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://legiscan.com/CT/bill/SB00058/2019|title=CT SB00058|work=LegiScan|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the aftermath of the [[2019 Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress crash]], which resulted in seven deaths and six injuries, Lamont was joined with Senator [[Richard Blumenthal]] in offering condolences to the families affected and ensuring them that the [[NTSB]] would launch a thorough investigation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/plane-crash-at-bradley-airport-boeing-b-17-flying-fortress-crashes-connecticut-today-live-updates/|title=World War II-era bomber plane crashes at Bradley Airport in Connecticut; fatalities confirmed |work=CBS News|first=Brian|last=Pascus|date=October 2, 2019|accessdate=November 15, 2019}}</ref> Lamont later met with the first responders to thank them for their service.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcconnecticut.com/news/local/Governor-Thanks-B17-Survivor-and-Responding-Air-National-Guard-Members-564126821.html|title=Governor Thanks B17 Survivor and Responding Air National Guard Members|work=NBC Connecticut|first=Caitlin|last=Burchill|date=October 30, 2019|accessdate=November 15, 2019}}</ref>  \n\n'''Approval ratings'''\n\nSince being elected governor, Connecticut residents have viewed Lamont unfavorably. [[Morning Consult]] has listed him among the top ten least popular governors every quarter since his election. In a survey conducted in the last quarter of 2019, he was ranked the fourth most unpopular governor in the United States, with a 51% disapproval rating and a 32% approval rating.<ref name=MorningConsult>{{cite web|url=https://morningconsult.com/governor-rankings/|title=Morning Consult's Governor Approval Ratings|work=[[Morning Consult]]|date=April 2019|accessdate=May 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn September 10, 1983,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/07/17/style/ann-huntress-to-wed-em-lamont-jr.html|title=Ann Huntress to Wed E.M. Lamont Jr.|date=July 17, 1983|work=The New York Times|accessdate=October 22, 2018}}</ref> Lamont married [[Ann Lamont|Ann Huntress]], a [[venture capital]]ist and managing partner at [[Oak Investment Partners]].<ref name=\"moffly\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/16/nyregion/16wife.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|title=Not-So-Hidden Asset, His Wife, Is Force in Lamont's Senate Bid|date=October 16, 2006|accessdate=February 8, 2013|first=Alison Leigh|last=Cowan|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> They have three children: Emily, Lindsay, and Teddy.<ref name=\"moffly\"/> He and his family live in [[Greenwich, Connecticut|Greenwich]] and have a [[vacation home]] in [[North Haven, Maine]].<ref name=\"Kershaw\"/>\n\nThe [[Lamont Gallery]] on the campus of [[Phillips Exeter Academy]] and the [[Lamont Library]] at [[Harvard University]] are both named in honor of his family.<ref name=\"Kershaw\"/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notes}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n{{Wikinews category}}\n* [https://portal.ct.gov/Office-of-the-Governor Governor Ned Lamont] official government website\n* {{Ballotpedia}}\n* {{C-SPAN|nedlamont02}}\n* {{imdb name|2331703}}\n* [http://www.ontheissues.org/Senate/Ned_Lamont.htm Ned Lamont] at [[On the Issues]]\n* {{CongLinks|votesmart=68381}}\n* {{worldcat id|lccn-no2012139378|Ned Lamont}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Joe Lieberman]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[United States Senator|U.S. Senator]] from [[Connecticut]]<br>([[Classes of United States Senators|Class 1]])|years=[[United States Senate election in Connecticut, 2006|2006]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Chris Murphy]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dannel Malloy|Dan Malloy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[List of governors of Connecticut|Governor of Connecticut]]|years=[[2018 Connecticut gubernatorial election|2018]]}}\n{{s-inc|recent}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dannel Malloy|Dan Malloy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of governors of Connecticut|Governor of Connecticut]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Mike Pence]]|as=[[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]]}}\n{{s-ttl|rows=2|title=[[United States order of precedence|Order of Precedence of the United States]]|years=Within Connecticut}}\n{{s-aft|after=Mayor of city<br>in which event is held}}\n|-\n{{s-aft|after=Otherwise {{Incumbent U.S. House Speaker}}<br>{{nowrap|{{small|''as [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives]]''}}}}}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Brian Kemp]]|as=[[Governor of Georgia]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States order of precedence|Order of Precedence of the United States]]|years=Outside Connecticut}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Charlie Baker]]|as=[[Governor of Massachusetts]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Governors of Connecticut}}\n{{Current U.S. Governors}}\n{{Current Connecticut statewide political officials}}\n{{portal bar|Biography|Connecticut|Politics}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lamont, Ned}}\n[[Category:Ned Lamont|*]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century American newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American anti\u2013Iraq War activists]]\n[[Category:Brookings Institution]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Greenwich, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Central Connecticut State University faculty]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Editors of Vermont newspapers]]\n[[Category:Governors of Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Harvard College alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Institute of Politics]]\n[[Category:Lamont family|n]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Laurel Hollow, New York]]\n[[Category:People from Ludlow, Vermont]]\n[[Category:People from North Haven, Maine]]\n[[Category:Phillips Exeter Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Yale School of Management alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Woko Sapien", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ned_Lamont"}
{"title_page": "William F. Prisk", "text_new": "{{short description|American executive and politician from California}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = William F. Prisk\n|image         = \n|birth_date    = {{birth date |1870|04|02}}\n|birth_place   = [[Grass Valley, California]]\n|death_date    = {{death_date|1962|12|21|1870|04|02}}\n|death_place   = [[Grass Valley, California]]\n|occupation    = newspaper executive, politician \n}}\n'''William Frederick Prisk, Jr.''' (April 2, 1870 \u2013 December 21, 1962) was a California newspaper executive and a politician from California. \n\n== Early life ==\nPrist was born in [[Grass Valley, California]].<ref name=\"norcalmediamuseum.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.norcalmediamuseum.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=87&Itemid=125|title=William F. Prisk|publisher=Media Museum of Northern California|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> Prisk's father was William Prisk, a miner. Prisk's mother was Mary (Hosking) Prisk. Prisk's parents were natives of [[Camborne]], [[Cornwall]], [[England]], who settled in  [[Grass Valley, California]].<ref name=\"White1967\">{{cite book|last=White|first=James Terry|title=The National cyclopaedia of American biography: being the history of the United States as illustrated in the lives of the founders, builders, and defenders of the republic, and of the men and women who are doing the work and moulding the thought of the present time|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zAvYAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=2 January 2012|year=1967|publisher=University Microfilms|page=40}}</ref> \n\n== Career ==\nPrisk held posts on the ''Grass Valley Union'' (editor and publisher), ''Evening Telegraph'' (publisher, typesetter, reporter and business manager), ''[[Pasadena Star-News]]'' (co-owner with his brother [[Charles H. Prisk]]), ''[[Long Beach, California|Long Beach]] [[Press-Telegram]]'' (editor-publisher). He was elected to the [[California State Senate]] in 1897, and at the time, was the youngest member of the [[California State Legislature]].   For his many years as editor-publisher of the ''Press-Telegram'', he received the nickname \"Mr. Long Beach\".<ref name=\"Healey1978\">{{cite book|last=Healey|first=John|title=Editors West: California Press Association, Newspaper Hall of Fame|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5VI_AAAAIAAJ|accessdate=2 January 2012|year=1978|publisher=Journalism Dept., California Polytechnic State University|page=26}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPrisk became a naturalized US citizen in 1869.<ref name=\"Payton2005\">{{cite book|last=Payton|first=Philip|title=The Cornish overseas: a history of Cornwall's 'great emigration'|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9Uc4gIhnSUkC&pg=PA215|accessdate=2 January 2012|date=15 April 2005|publisher=Dundurn Press Ltd.|isbn=978-1-904880-04-2|pages=215\u2013}}</ref> Three years after his death in Long Beach, he was selected to the [[California Newspaper Publishers Association]]'s Newspaper Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"Wyckoff2007\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theunion.com/article/20070714/NEWS/107140139|title=Nevada County's Hall of Fame: William F. Prisk, publisher By Bob Wyckoff|last=Wyckoff|first=Bob |date=July 14, 2007|publisher=The Union|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> \n\n== Legacy ==\nThe William F. Prisk Elementary School in the \n[[Long Beach Unified School District]] is named in his honor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prisk-lbusd-ca.schoolloop.com/cms/page_view?d=x&piid=&vpid=1267281172098|title=William F. Prisk |author=William F. Prisk Elementary School |work=Historic Resources report Press-Telegram and Meeker/Baker Buildings Long Beach, CA 31 July 2006, rev 15 August 2006, and California Newspaper Hall of Fame.|publisher=Long Beach Unified School District |accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Partial works==\n* ''1895 pictorial history of Nevada County, California''\n* ''Nevada county mining review''\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Prisk, William F.}}\n[[Category:1870 births]]\n[[Category:1962 deaths]]\n[[Category:California state senators]]\n[[Category:Editors of California newspapers]]\n[[Category:American newspaper publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:People from Grass Valley, California]]\n[[Category:People from Long Beach, California]]\n[[Category:People with acquired American citizenship]]\n[[Category:People from Camborne]]\n[[Category:Journalists from California]]\n[[Category:Cornish emigrants to the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American executive and politician from California}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = William F. Prisk\n|image         = \n|birth_date    = {{birth date |1870|04|02}}\n|birth_place   = [[Grass Valley, California]]\n|death_date    = {{death_date|1962|12|21|1870|04|02}}\n|death_place   = [[Grass Valley, California]]\n|occupation    = newspaper executive, politician \n}}\n'''William Frederick Prisk, Jr.''' (April 2, 1870 \u2013 December 21, 1962) was a California newspaper executive and a politician from California. \n\n== Early life ==\nPrist was born in [[Grass Valley, California]].<ref name=\"norcalmediamuseum.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.norcalmediamuseum.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=87&Itemid=125|title=William F. Prisk|publisher=Media Museum of Northern California|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> Prisk's father was William Prisk, a miner. Prisk's mother was Mary (Hosking) Prisk. Prisk's parents were natives of [[Camborne]], [[Cornwall]], [[England]], who settled in  [[Grass Valley, California]].<ref name=\"White1967\">{{cite book|last=White|first=James Terry|title=The National cyclopaedia of American biography: being the history of the United States as illustrated in the lives of the founders, builders, and defenders of the republic, and of the men and women who are doing the work and moulding the thought of the present time|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zAvYAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=2 January 2012|year=1967|publisher=University Microfilms|page=40}}</ref> \n\n== Career ==\nPrisk held posts on the ''Grass Valley Union'' (editor and publisher), ''Evening Telegraph'' (publisher, typesetter, reporter and business manager), ''[[Pasadena Star-News]]'' (co-owner with his brother [[Charles H. Prisk]]), ''[[Long Beach, California|Long Beach]] [[Press-Telegram]]'' (editor-publisher). He was elected to the [[California State Senate]] in 1897, and at the time, was the youngest member of the [[California State Legislature]].   For his many years as editor-publisher of the ''Press-Telegram'', he received the nickname \"Mr. Long Beach\".<ref name=\"Healey1978\">{{cite book|last=Healey|first=John|title=Editors West: California Press Association, Newspaper Hall of Fame|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5VI_AAAAIAAJ|accessdate=2 January 2012|year=1978|publisher=Journalism Dept., California Polytechnic State University|page=26}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPrisk became a naturalized US citizen in 1869.<ref name=\"Payton2005\">{{cite book|last=Payton|first=Philip|title=The Cornish overseas: a history of Cornwall's 'great emigration'|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9Uc4gIhnSUkC&pg=PA215|accessdate=2 January 2012|date=15 April 2005|publisher=Dundurn Press Ltd.|isbn=978-1-904880-04-2|pages=215\u2013}}</ref> Three years after his death in Long Beach, he was selected to the [[California Newspaper Publishers Association]]'s Newspaper Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"Wyckoff2007\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theunion.com/article/20070714/NEWS/107140139|title=Nevada County's Hall of Fame: William F. Prisk, publisher By Bob Wyckoff|last=Wyckoff|first=Bob |date=July 14, 2007|publisher=The Union|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> \n\n== Legacy ==\nThe William F. Prisk Elementary School in the \n[[Long Beach Unified School District]] is named in his honor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prisk-lbusd-ca.schoolloop.com/cms/page_view?d=x&piid=&vpid=1267281172098|title=William F. Prisk |author=William F. Prisk Elementary School |work=Historic Resources report Press-Telegram and Meeker/Baker Buildings Long Beach, CA 31 July 2006, rev 15 August 2006, and California Newspaper Hall of Fame.|publisher=Long Beach Unified School District |accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Partial works==\n* ''1895 pictorial history of Nevada County, California''\n* ''Nevada county mining review''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Prisk, William F.}}\n[[Category:1870 births]]\n[[Category:1962 deaths]]\n[[Category:California state senators]]\n[[Category:Editors of California newspapers]]\n[[Category:American newspaper publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:People from Grass Valley, California]]\n[[Category:People from Long Beach, California]]\n[[Category:People with acquired American citizenship]]\n[[Category:People from Camborne]]\n[[Category:Journalists from California]]\n[[Category:Cornish emigrants to the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Gazamp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:AddedPortal:Cornwall", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_F._Prisk"}
{"title_page": "Grand Theft Auto 2", "text_new": "{{short description|1999 action-adventure game}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Grand Theft Auto 2\n| image = GTA2 Box art.jpg\n| developer = {{Unbulleted list|[[DMA Design]]|[[Tarantula Studios]] {{small|(GBC)}}}}\n| publisher = [[Rockstar Games]]\n| series = ''[[Grand Theft Auto]]''\n| platforms = {{Unbulleted list|[[Microsoft Windows]]|[[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]]|[[Dreamcast]]|[[Game Boy Color]]}}\n| released = {{Collapsible list|title=22 October 1999|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;background:transparent;text-align:left|'''Microsoft Windows''', '''PlayStation'''|22 October 1999<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Take-Two+Interactive+Software+Inc.%27s+Rockstar+Games+Division+...-a056248278|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203055514/https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Take-Two+Interactive+Software+Inc.'s+Rockstar+Games+Division+...-a056248278|title=Take-Two Interactive Software Inc.'s Rockstar Games Division Announces its GTA2 has Gone Gold and Will Ship Worldwide on October 22|website=[[Business Wire]]|publisher=[[Berkshire Hathaway]]|archivedate=December 3, 2018|date=October 13, 1999|accessdate=July 8, 2019|via=[[TheFreeDictionary.com]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Sam|last=Kennedy|url=http://headline.gamespot.com/news/99_10/13_vg_gta/index.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000416145000/http://headline.gamespot.com/news/99_10/13_vg_gta/index.html|title=Rockstar's GTA2 Goes Gold|website=[[GameSpot]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|archivedate=April 16, 2000|date=October 13, 1999|accessdate=July 8, 2019}}</ref><br />'''Dreamcast'''{{Video game release|NA|1 May 2000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Take-Two+Interactive+Software%2C+Inc.%27s+Rockstar+Games+Launches+GTA2...-a061826045|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203055443/https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Take-Two+Interactive+Software%2C+Inc.%27s+Rockstar+Games+Launches+GTA2...-a061826045|title=Take-Two Interactive Software, Inc.'s Rockstar Games Launches GTA2 For the Sega Dreamcast; Grand Theft Auto Franchise Makes Sega System Debut|website=[[Business Wire]]|publisher=[[Berkshire Hathaway]]|via=[[TheFreeDictionary.com]]|archivedate=December 3, 2018|date=May 1, 2000|accessdate=July 8, 2019}}</ref>|EU|28 July 2000}}'''Game Boy Color'''{{Video game release|NA|December 2000|EU|10 November 2000}}}}\n| genre = [[Action-adventure game|Action-adventure]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]\n| director = {{Unbulleted list|Jim Woods|[[David Jones (video game developer)|David Jones]]|Simon Crisp {{small|(GBC)}}}}\n| designer = {{Unbulleted list|Stephen Banks|William Mills|Billy Thomson}}\n| programmer = {{Unbulleted list|Keith R. Hamilton|Martin McKenzie {{small|(GBC)}}}}\n| artist = {{Unbulleted list|Ian McQue|Russell East {{small|(GBC)}}}}\n| writer = [[Dan Houser]]\n| composer = {{Unbulleted list|Colin Anderson|Craig Conner|Bert Reid|Stuart Ross|Paul Scargill|Anthony Paton {{small|(GBC)}}}}\n}}\n'''''Grand Theft Auto 2''''' is an [[action-adventure game]], developed by [[DMA Design]] and published by [[Rockstar Games]], for [[Microsoft Windows]] and the [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]] in October 1999, and the [[Dreamcast]] and [[Game Boy Color]] in 2000. It is the sequel to 1997's ''[[Grand Theft Auto (video game)|Grand Theft Auto]]'', and the second installment of the [[Grand Theft Auto|''Grand Theft Auto'' series]]. The game focuses on players taking on the role of a criminal as they roam a fictional futuristic city, conducting jobs for various crime syndicates and having free reign to do whatever they wish to achieve their goal. The game's intro is unique for a title in the series, as it involved live-action scenes filmed by Rockstar Games.\n\nThe game received mixed reviews from critics, though the GBC version fared the worst, but was a modest commercial success. ''Grand Theft Auto 2'' was succeed by ''[[Grand Theft Auto III]]'' in October 2001, while the game itself was re-released on [[Steam (software)|Steam]] in January 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://store.steampowered.com/news/1395/ |title=News \u2013 Rockstar Games Brings Full Line-up to Steam |author=[[Steam (software)|Steam]] |publisher=[[Valve Corporation|Valve]] |date=4 January 2008 |accessdate=5 February 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100820162759/http://store.steampowered.com/news/1395 |archivedate=20 August 2010 }}</ref>\n\n== Gameplay ==\n[[Image:GTA2 PC in-game screenshot.jpg|thumb|left|''Grand Theft Auto 2'' being played at \"dusk\" in the Windows version.]]\nLike its predecessor ''Grand Theft Auto'', the game focuses on players completing a series of levels, each requiring a set target [[Score (game)#Video games|score]] being achieved in order to progress to the next stage. Points are awarded from various criminal actions such as destroying cars, selling vehicles, and completing [[Quest (video gaming)|missions]] for various crime syndicates, with the latter awarding more points than doing simple criminal actions. Unlike its predecessor, ''Grand Theft Auto 2'' is set in an unspecified time period - conflicting sources suggest anything from \"three weeks into the future\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockstargames.com/gta2/frameset.html |title=GTA2 \u2013 Frameset |publisher=[[Rockstar Games]] |date= |accessdate=5 February 2011 }}</ref> to the year to be 2013,<ref name=\"rockstargames.com\"/> despite in-game references - and within a [[Retrofuturism|retrofuturistic]] metropolis referred to only as \"Anywhere, USA\",<ref name=\"rockstargames.com\">{{cite web | url=http://www.rockstargames.com/gta2/journal/journal_list.html | title=GTA2 \u2013 Individual Police Files |publisher=[[Rockstar Games]] |accessdate=29 April 2007 }}</ref> with each level focused on a different district of the city. Completing jobs earns points and a multiplier bonus, while failing them earns nothing. Creating chaos from their crimes will cause the player to be wanted by the police who will hound the player to arrest or kill them, with higher wanted levels increasing the level of response used. Being arrested or dying loses the player any equipment they found, and impacts their multiplier bonus.\n\n''Grand Theft Auto 2'' introduced several new features and improvements to the game. Players can now [[Saved game|save their game]] during a playthrough of a level by visiting the church they start at, but must pay a set amount of points to do so. Jobs on offer come from three different syndicates - each level features two unique syndicates, alongside a third syndicate present in all levels. By doing jobs for a syndicate and successfully completing it, the player gains respect with that syndicate, allowing them to take on tougher jobs with enough respect, but lose it with their chief rivals, locking them out of their jobs and making the syndicate's members hostile to the player. Other improvements include vehicles and pedestrians being more interactive with the game's environment - such as gang members engaging in fights with police - the presence of other criminals (such as muggers),<ref name=\"IGN\">{{cite web|url=http://uk.pc.ign.com/articles/161/161648p1.html |title=Grand Theft Auto 2 \u2013 IGN |last=Blevins |first=Tal |website=[[IGN]] |date=18 November 1999 |accessdate=29 April 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080213210410/http://uk.pc.ign.com/articles/161/161648p1.html |archivedate=13 February 2008 }}</ref> a [[Health (gaming)|health meter]], garages that can modify vehicles with special improvements, a selection of side missions ranging from running a taxi to driving a semi-truck, and groups of 'hidden' [[Item (gaming)|packages]] to find across the level.\n\n== ''GTA 2 \u2013 The Movie'' ==\nThe game was developed with an eight-minute [[short film]] of [[live-action]] footage, filmed within New York City. The movie was devised as an introductory sequence for the game, and was made available on [[Rockstar Games]]'s website. The film focuses on the exploit of a criminal named Claude Speed ([[Scott Maslen]]), who conducts jobs around Anywhere City, before being killed by an assassin from one of the syndicates. The film was based on a screenplay by [[Dan Houser]], and directed by [[Alex De Rakoff]].{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n\nEach area features five radio stations from a pool of eleven, one of which is heard as the player drives most vehicles in game. Changing radio stations for preference is possible. \"Head Radio\" was present in the original ''Grand Theft Auto'', ''Grand Theft Auto III'' and ''Grand Theft Auto: Liberty City Stories''. Each gang has its own radio station that transmits within a limited area. Police vehicles, ambulances, fire trucks and tanks had no ability to listen to the radio channels. Instead, the player would hear the radio transmitter of the emergency services.\n\nAll the [[Video game music|music]] and the ads included in the game are exclusive, following the tradition of previous games. People in charge of the musical content were Craig Conner, Stuart Ross, Paul Scargill, Colin Anderson, Bert Reid and [[Moving Shadow]]. Some of these producers would keep their work on subsequent GTA releases.\n\nThe Game Boy Color version uses some real songs, one of which is a sped up version of [[Back in Black (song)|Back in Black]] by [[AC/DC]]. The Character Selection theme is an old Brazilian song titled \"[[Chega de Saudade]]\".\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Video game reviews\n| GR = 71.50% (PC)<ref name=\"GR PC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerankings.com/pc/197478-grand-theft-auto-2/index.html |title=Grand Theft Auto 2 for PC |accessdate=12 August 2012 |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120620024652/http://www.gamerankings.com/pc/197478-grand-theft-auto-2/index.html |archivedate=20 June 2012 }}</ref><br />70.80% (DC)<ref name=\"GR DC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerankings.com/dreamcast/197479-grand-theft-auto-2/index.html |title=Grand Theft Auto 2 for Dreamcast |accessdate=12 August 2012 |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120830094948/http://www.gamerankings.com/dreamcast/197479-grand-theft-auto-2/index.html |archivedate=30 August 2012 }}</ref><br />69.92% (PS1)<ref name=\"GR PS1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerankings.com/ps/185853-grand-theft-auto-2/index.html |title=Grand Theft Auto 2 for PlayStation |accessdate=12 August 2012 |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120905210433/http://www.gamerankings.com/ps/185853-grand-theft-auto-2/index.html |archivedate=5 September 2012 }}</ref><br />35.00% (GBC)<ref name=\"GR GBC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerankings.com/gbc/562989-grand-theft-auto-2/index.html |title=Grand Theft Auto 2 for Game Boy Color |accessdate=12 August 2012 |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120809001631/http://www.gamerankings.com/gbc/562989-grand-theft-auto-2/index.html |archivedate=9 August 2012 }}</ref>\n| MC = 70/100 (PS1)<ref name=\"MC PS1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation/grand-theft-auto-2 |title=Grand Theft Auto 2 for PlayStation Reviews |accessdate=13 February 2013 |website=[[Metacritic]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130430224838/http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation/grand-theft-auto-2 |archivedate=30 April 2013 }}</ref>\n| GSpot = 6.9/10 (PS1)<ref name=\"GSpot PS\">{{cite web|url=http://au.gamespot.com/grand-theft-auto-2/platform/ps/ |title=Grand Theft Auto 2 - GameSpot.com |accessdate=13 February 2013 |website=[[GameSpot]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130303104321/http://au.gamespot.com/grand-theft-auto-2/platform/ps/ |archivedate=3 March 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><br/>6.9/10 (DC)<ref name=\"GSpot DC\">{{cite web|url=http://au.gamespot.com/grand-theft-auto-2/platform/dreamcast/ |title=Grand Theft Auto 2 - GameSpot.com |accessdate=13 February 2013 |website=[[GameSpot]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130129180320/http://au.gamespot.com/grand-theft-auto-2/platform/dreamcast/ |archivedate=29 January 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><br/>6.8/10 (PC)<ref name=\"GSpot PC\">{{cite web|url=http://au.gamespot.com/grand-theft-auto-2/ |title=Grand Theft Auto 2 - GameSpot.com |accessdate=13 February 2013 |website=[[GameSpot]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130129182728/http://au.gamespot.com/grand-theft-auto-2/ |archivedate=29 January 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| IGN = 7.3/10 (PC)<ref name=\"IGN\"/><br/>6.8/10 (PS1)<br/>6.7/10 (DC)\n| Edge = 8/10<ref name=\"Edge review\"/>\n| NGen = {{rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"NG\"/>\n}}\n\n''Grand Theft Auto 2''{{'}}s computer version received a \"Silver\" sales award from the [[Entertainment and Leisure Software Publishers Association]] (ELSPA),<ref name=silverelspa>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221154943/http://www.elspa.com/?i=3942 |url=http://www.elspa.com:80/?i=3942 |title=ELSPA Sales Awards: Silver |work=[[Entertainment and Leisure Software Publishers Association]] |archivedate=21 February 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref> indicating sales of at least 100,000 copies in the United Kingdom.<ref name=gamasutrasales>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170918063107/https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/112220/ELSPA_Wii_Fit_Mario_Kart_Reach_Diamond_Status_In_UK.php |url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/112220/ELSPA_Wii_Fit_Mario_Kart_Reach_Diamond_Status_In_UK.php |title=ELSPA: ''Wii Fit'', ''Mario Kart'' Reach Diamond Status In UK | author=Caoili, Eric | date=26 November 2008 |work=[[Gamasutra]] |archivedate=18 September 2017 |url-status=dead}}</ref> The game's PlayStation version received a \"Platinum\" sales award (300,000 or more units in the United Kingdom) from ELSPA.<ref name=platinumelspa>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090515224703/http://www.elspa.com/?i=3944 |url=http://www.elspa.com:80/?i=3944 |title=ELSPA Sales Awards: Platinum |work=[[Entertainment and Leisure Software Publishers Association]] |archivedate=15 May 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n''Grand Theft Auto 2'' was released to mixed reviews.<ref name=\"MC PS1\"/> The game's graphics received mixed reactions from critics, who noted that they had barely any difference to the graphics in the [[Grand Theft Auto (video game)|original game]]. [[IGN]]'s Tal Blevins called them \"average at best\", and that the scenery is \"hard to appreciate\".<ref name=\"IGN\"/> Jeff Gerstmann of [[GameSpot]] said that the \"graphics look a bit plain.\"<ref name=\"GSpot\"/> The game's soundtrack received positive feedback, with Jeff Gerstmann calling it a \"great soundtrack\", and that it \"closely [mirrors] the station-style of the original game.<ref name=\"GSpot\">{{cite web|url=http://au.gamespot.com/grand-theft-auto-2/reviews/grand-theft-auto-2-review-2545965/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130826091059/http://au.gamespot.com/grand-theft-auto-2/reviews/grand-theft-auto-2-review-2545965/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=26 August 2013 |title=Grand Theft Auto 2 Review - GameSpot.com |last=Gerstmann |first=Jeff |website=[[GameSpot]] |date=22 October 1999 |accessdate=26 August 2013 }}</ref> Tal Blevins of IGN called it \"one of the best features\" of the game.<ref name=\"IGN\"/>\n\n''Grand Theft Auto 2''{{'}}s gameplay elements received mixed reactions. IGN's Jeremy Dunham said that the gameplay is \"where the game really takes a punch to the stomach\", and that it \"could've been a lot better.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://au.ign.com/articles/2000/05/09/grand-theft-auto-2-review |title=Grand Theft Auto 2 Review \u2013 IGN |last=Dunham |first=Jeremy |date=8 May 2000 |accessdate=26 August 2013 }}</ref> Tal Blevins called it \"simple, but effective.\"<ref name=\"IGN\"/> Jeff Gerstmann said that \"even though the gameplay is largely the same as in the previous ''GTA'', it's still a lot of fun.\"<ref name=\"GSpot\"/> ''[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]'' highlighted the game's story development and inventive missions, stating that ''Grand Theft Auto 2'' \"manages to draw you deep into the complexities of its world\".<ref name=\"Edge review\">{{cite magazine |title=Grand Theft Auto 2 |magazine=[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]] |publisher=[[Future Publishing]] |issue=79 |pages=80\u201381 |date=December 1999}}</ref>\n\nBlake Fischer reviewed the Dreamcast version of the game for ''[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]'', rating it two stars out of five, and stated that \"A great idea that, for one reason or another, never really gets into a must-play game.\"<ref name=\"NG\">{{cite magazine|last=Fischer|first=Blake|title=Finals|magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|volume=3|issue=8|publisher=[[Future US|Imagine Media]]|date=August 2000|page=90}}</ref>\n\n{{-}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Notelist}}\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|last1=Loguidice|first1=Bill|last2=Barton|first2=Matt|title=Vintage Games: An Insider Look at the History of Grand Theft Auto, Super Mario, and the Most Influential Games of All Time|date=2012|publisher=[[Taylor & Francis]]|isbn=1136137572|page=161|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TEp5AgAAQBAJ&pg=PT161|accessdate=6 January 2018}}\n*{{cite book|first=Nate|last=Garrelts|authorlink=Nate Garrelts|title=[[The Meaning and Culture of Grand Theft Auto]]|date=2006|publisher=[[McFarland & Company|McFarland]]|location=Jefferson, North Carolina, United States|isbn=9780786428229|issn=|page=}}\n*{{cite book|first=David|last=Kushner|authorlink=David Kushner|title=Jacked: The Outlaw Story of Grand Theft Auto|date=2012|publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons|Wiley]]|location=Hoboken, New Jersey, United States|isbn=0470936371|issn=|page=}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|www.rockstargames.com/gta2/}}\n\n{{Grand Theft Auto}}\n{{DMA Design}}\n{{Rockstar Games}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grand Theft Auto 02}}\n[[Category:1999 video games]]\n[[Category:Action-adventure games]]\n[[Category:Dreamcast games]]\n[[Category:Freeware games]]\n[[Category:Game Boy Color games]]\n[[Category:Grand Theft Auto]]\n[[Category:Open world video games]]\n[[Category:Organized crime video games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation (console) games]]\n[[Category:Rockstar Games]]\n[[Category:Top-down video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Video game sequels]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Video games set in 2013]]\n[[Category:Video games set in the United States]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Retrofuturistic video games]]\n[[Category:Cancelled Nintendo 64 games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1999 action-adventure game}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Grand Theft Auto 2\n| image = GTA2 Box art.jpg\n| developer = {{Unbulleted list|[[DMA Design]]|[[Tarantula Studios]] {{small|(GBC)}}}}\n| publisher = [[Rockstar Games]]\n| series = ''[[Grand Theft Auto]]''\n| platforms = {{Unbulleted list|[[Microsoft Windows]]|[[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]]|[[Dreamcast]]|[[Game Boy Color]]}}\n| released = {{Collapsible list|title=22 October 1999|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;background:transparent;text-align:left|'''Microsoft Windows''', '''PlayStation'''|22 October 1999<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Take-Two+Interactive+Software+Inc.%27s+Rockstar+Games+Division+...-a056248278|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203055514/https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Take-Two+Interactive+Software+Inc.'s+Rockstar+Games+Division+...-a056248278|title=Take-Two Interactive Software Inc.'s Rockstar Games Division Announces its GTA2 has Gone Gold and Will Ship Worldwide on October 22|website=[[Business Wire]]|publisher=[[Berkshire Hathaway]]|archivedate=December 3, 2018|date=October 13, 1999|accessdate=July 8, 2019|via=[[TheFreeDictionary.com]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Sam|last=Kennedy|url=http://headline.gamespot.com/news/99_10/13_vg_gta/index.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000416145000/http://headline.gamespot.com/news/99_10/13_vg_gta/index.html|title=Rockstar's GTA2 Goes Gold|website=[[GameSpot]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|archivedate=April 16, 2000|date=October 13, 1999|accessdate=July 8, 2019}}</ref><br />'''Dreamcast'''{{Video game release|NA|1 May 2000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Take-Two+Interactive+Software%2C+Inc.%27s+Rockstar+Games+Launches+GTA2...-a061826045|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203055443/https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Take-Two+Interactive+Software%2C+Inc.%27s+Rockstar+Games+Launches+GTA2...-a061826045|title=Take-Two Interactive Software, Inc.'s Rockstar Games Launches GTA2 For the Sega Dreamcast; Grand Theft Auto Franchise Makes Sega System Debut|website=[[Business Wire]]|publisher=[[Berkshire Hathaway]]|via=[[TheFreeDictionary.com]]|archivedate=December 3, 2018|date=May 1, 2000|accessdate=July 8, 2019}}</ref>|EU|28 July 2000}}'''Game Boy Color'''{{Video game release|NA|December 2000|EU|10 November 2000}}}}\n| genre = [[Action-adventure game|Action-adventure]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]\n| director = {{Unbulleted list|Jim Woods|[[David Jones (video game developer)|David Jones]]|Simon Crisp {{small|(GBC)}}}}\n| designer = {{Unbulleted list|Stephen Banks|William Mills|Billy Thomson}}\n| programmer = {{Unbulleted list|Keith R. Hamilton|Martin McKenzie {{small|(GBC)}}}}\n| artist = {{Unbulleted list|Ian McQue|Russell East {{small|(GBC)}}}}\n| writer = [[Dan Houser]]\n| composer = {{Unbulleted list|Colin Anderson|Craig Conner|Bert Reid|Stuart Ross|Paul Scargill|Anthony Paton {{small|(GBC)}}}}\n}}\n'''''Grand Theft Auto 2''''' is an [[action-adventure game]], developed by [[DMA Design]] and published by [[Rockstar Games]], for [[Microsoft Windows]] and the [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]] in October 1999, and the [[Dreamcast]] and [[Game Boy Color]] in 2000. It is the sequel to 1997's ''[[Grand Theft Auto (video game)|Grand Theft Auto]]'', and the second installment of the [[Grand Theft Auto|''Grand Theft Auto'' series]]. The game focuses on players taking on the role of a criminal as they roam a fictional futuristic city, conducting jobs for various crime syndicates and having free reign to do whatever they wish to achieve their goal. The game's intro is unique for a title in the series, as it involved live-action scenes filmed by Rockstar Games.\n\nThe game received mixed reviews from critics, though the GBC version fared the worst, but was a modest commercial success. ''Grand Theft Auto 2'' was succeed by ''[[Grand Theft Auto III]]'' in October 2001, while the game itself was re-released on [[Steam (software)|Steam]] in January 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://store.steampowered.com/news/1395/ |title=News \u2013 Rockstar Games Brings Full Line-up to Steam |author=[[Steam (software)|Steam]] |publisher=[[Valve Corporation|Valve]] |date=4 January 2008 |accessdate=5 February 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100820162759/http://store.steampowered.com/news/1395 |archivedate=20 August 2010 }}</ref>\n\n== Gameplay ==\n[[Image:GTA2 PC in-game screenshot.jpg|thumb|left|''Grand Theft Auto 2'' being played at \"dusk\" in the Windows version.]]\nLike its predecessor ''Grand Theft Auto'', the game focuses on players completing a series of levels, each requiring a set target [[Score (game)#Video games|score]] being achieved in order to progress to the next stage. Points are awarded from various criminal actions such as destroying cars, selling vehicles, and completing [[Quest (video gaming)|missions]] for various crime syndicates, with the latter awarding more points than doing simple criminal actions. Unlike its predecessor, ''Grand Theft Auto 2'' is set in an unspecified time period - conflicting sources suggest anything from \"three weeks into the future\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockstargames.com/gta2/frameset.html |title=GTA2 \u2013 Frameset |publisher=[[Rockstar Games]] |date= |accessdate=5 February 2011 }}</ref> to the year to be 2013,<ref name=\"rockstargames.com\"/> despite in-game references - and within a [[Retrofuturism|retrofuturistic]] metropolis referred to only as \"Anywhere, USA\",<ref name=\"rockstargames.com\">{{cite web | url=http://www.rockstargames.com/gta2/journal/journal_list.html | title=GTA2 \u2013 Individual Police Files |publisher=[[Rockstar Games]] |accessdate=29 April 2007 }}</ref> with each level focused on a different district of the city. Completing jobs earns points and a multiplier bonus, while failing them earns nothing. Creating chaos from their crimes will cause the player to be wanted by the police who will hound the player to arrest or kill them, with higher wanted levels increasing the level of response used. Being arrested or dying loses the player any equipment they found, and impacts their multiplier bonus.\n\n''Grand Theft Auto 2'' introduced several new features and improvements to the game. Players can now [[Saved game|save their game]] during a playthrough of a level by visiting the church they start at, but must pay a set amount of points to do so. Jobs on offer come from three different syndicates - each level features two unique syndicates, alongside a third syndicate present in all levels. By doing jobs for a syndicate and successfully completing it, the player gains respect with that syndicate, allowing them to take on tougher jobs with enough respect, but lose it with their chief rivals, locking them out of their jobs and making the syndicate's members hostile to the player. Other improvements include vehicles and pedestrians being more interactive with the game's environment - such as gang members engaging in fights with police - the presence of other criminals (such as muggers),<ref name=\"IGN\">{{cite web|url=http://uk.pc.ign.com/articles/161/161648p1.html |title=Grand Theft Auto 2 \u2013 IGN |last=Blevins |first=Tal |website=[[IGN]] |date=18 November 1999 |accessdate=29 April 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080213210410/http://uk.pc.ign.com/articles/161/161648p1.html |archivedate=13 February 2008 }}</ref> a [[Health (gaming)|health meter]], garages that can modify vehicles with special improvements, a selection of side missions ranging from running a taxi to driving a semi-truck, and groups of 'hidden' [[Item (gaming)|packages]] to find across the level.\n\n== ''GTA 2 \u2013 The Movie'' ==\nThe game was developed with an eight-minute [[short film]] of [[live-action]] footage, filmed within New York City. The movie was devised as an introductory sequence for the game, and was made available on [[Rockstar Games]]'s website. The film focuses on the exploit of a criminal named Claude Speed ([[Scott Maslen]]), who conducts jobs around Anywhere City, before being killed by an assassin from one of the syndicates. The film was based on a screenplay [[Dan Houser]] and directed by [[Alex De Rakoff]].{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n\nEach area features five radio stations from a pool of eleven, one of which is heard as the player drives most vehicles in game. Changing radio stations for preference is possible. \"Head Radio\" was present in the original ''Grand Theft Auto'', ''Grand Theft Auto III'' and ''Grand Theft Auto: Liberty City Stories''. Each gang has its own radio station that transmits within a limited area. Police vehicles, ambulances, fire trucks and tanks had no ability to listen to the radio channels. Instead, the player would hear the radio transmitter of the emergency services.\n\nAll the [[Video game music|music]] and the ads included in the game are exclusive, following the tradition of previous games. People in charge of the musical content were Craig Conner, Stuart Ross, Paul Scargill, Colin Anderson, Bert Reid and [[Moving Shadow]]. Some of these producers would keep their work on subsequent GTA releases.\n\nThe Game Boy Color version uses some real songs, one of which is a sped up version of [[Back in Black (song)|Back in Black]] by [[AC/DC]]. The Character Selection theme is an old Brazilian song titled \"[[Chega de Saudade]]\".\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Video game reviews\n| GR = 71.50% (PC)<ref name=\"GR PC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerankings.com/pc/197478-grand-theft-auto-2/index.html |title=Grand Theft Auto 2 for PC |accessdate=12 August 2012 |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120620024652/http://www.gamerankings.com/pc/197478-grand-theft-auto-2/index.html |archivedate=20 June 2012 }}</ref><br />70.80% (DC)<ref name=\"GR DC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerankings.com/dreamcast/197479-grand-theft-auto-2/index.html |title=Grand Theft Auto 2 for Dreamcast |accessdate=12 August 2012 |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120830094948/http://www.gamerankings.com/dreamcast/197479-grand-theft-auto-2/index.html |archivedate=30 August 2012 }}</ref><br />69.92% (PS1)<ref name=\"GR PS1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerankings.com/ps/185853-grand-theft-auto-2/index.html |title=Grand Theft Auto 2 for PlayStation |accessdate=12 August 2012 |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120905210433/http://www.gamerankings.com/ps/185853-grand-theft-auto-2/index.html |archivedate=5 September 2012 }}</ref><br />35.00% (GBC)<ref name=\"GR GBC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerankings.com/gbc/562989-grand-theft-auto-2/index.html |title=Grand Theft Auto 2 for Game Boy Color |accessdate=12 August 2012 |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120809001631/http://www.gamerankings.com/gbc/562989-grand-theft-auto-2/index.html |archivedate=9 August 2012 }}</ref>\n| MC = 70/100 (PS1)<ref name=\"MC PS1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation/grand-theft-auto-2 |title=Grand Theft Auto 2 for PlayStation Reviews |accessdate=13 February 2013 |website=[[Metacritic]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130430224838/http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation/grand-theft-auto-2 |archivedate=30 April 2013 }}</ref>\n| GSpot = 6.9/10 (PS1)<ref name=\"GSpot PS\">{{cite web|url=http://au.gamespot.com/grand-theft-auto-2/platform/ps/ |title=Grand Theft Auto 2 - GameSpot.com |accessdate=13 February 2013 |website=[[GameSpot]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130303104321/http://au.gamespot.com/grand-theft-auto-2/platform/ps/ |archivedate=3 March 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><br/>6.9/10 (DC)<ref name=\"GSpot DC\">{{cite web|url=http://au.gamespot.com/grand-theft-auto-2/platform/dreamcast/ |title=Grand Theft Auto 2 - GameSpot.com |accessdate=13 February 2013 |website=[[GameSpot]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130129180320/http://au.gamespot.com/grand-theft-auto-2/platform/dreamcast/ |archivedate=29 January 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><br/>6.8/10 (PC)<ref name=\"GSpot PC\">{{cite web|url=http://au.gamespot.com/grand-theft-auto-2/ |title=Grand Theft Auto 2 - GameSpot.com |accessdate=13 February 2013 |website=[[GameSpot]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130129182728/http://au.gamespot.com/grand-theft-auto-2/ |archivedate=29 January 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| IGN = 7.3/10 (PC)<ref name=\"IGN\"/><br/>6.8/10 (PS1)<br/>6.7/10 (DC)\n| Edge = 8/10<ref name=\"Edge review\"/>\n| NGen = {{rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"NG\"/>\n}}\n\n''Grand Theft Auto 2''{{'}}s computer version received a \"Silver\" sales award from the [[Entertainment and Leisure Software Publishers Association]] (ELSPA),<ref name=silverelspa>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221154943/http://www.elspa.com/?i=3942 |url=http://www.elspa.com:80/?i=3942 |title=ELSPA Sales Awards: Silver |work=[[Entertainment and Leisure Software Publishers Association]] |archivedate=21 February 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref> indicating sales of at least 100,000 copies in the United Kingdom.<ref name=gamasutrasales>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170918063107/https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/112220/ELSPA_Wii_Fit_Mario_Kart_Reach_Diamond_Status_In_UK.php |url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/112220/ELSPA_Wii_Fit_Mario_Kart_Reach_Diamond_Status_In_UK.php |title=ELSPA: ''Wii Fit'', ''Mario Kart'' Reach Diamond Status In UK | author=Caoili, Eric | date=26 November 2008 |work=[[Gamasutra]] |archivedate=18 September 2017 |url-status=dead}}</ref> The game's PlayStation version received a \"Platinum\" sales award (300,000 or more units in the United Kingdom) from ELSPA.<ref name=platinumelspa>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090515224703/http://www.elspa.com/?i=3944 |url=http://www.elspa.com:80/?i=3944 |title=ELSPA Sales Awards: Platinum |work=[[Entertainment and Leisure Software Publishers Association]] |archivedate=15 May 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n''Grand Theft Auto 2'' was released to mixed reviews.<ref name=\"MC PS1\"/> The game's graphics received mixed reactions from critics, who noted that they had barely any difference to the graphics in the [[Grand Theft Auto (video game)|original game]]. [[IGN]]'s Tal Blevins called them \"average at best\", and that the scenery is \"hard to appreciate\".<ref name=\"IGN\"/> Jeff Gerstmann of [[GameSpot]] said that the \"graphics look a bit plain.\"<ref name=\"GSpot\"/> The game's soundtrack received positive feedback, with Jeff Gerstmann calling it a \"great soundtrack\", and that it \"closely [mirrors] the station-style of the original game.<ref name=\"GSpot\">{{cite web|url=http://au.gamespot.com/grand-theft-auto-2/reviews/grand-theft-auto-2-review-2545965/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130826091059/http://au.gamespot.com/grand-theft-auto-2/reviews/grand-theft-auto-2-review-2545965/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=26 August 2013 |title=Grand Theft Auto 2 Review - GameSpot.com |last=Gerstmann |first=Jeff |website=[[GameSpot]] |date=22 October 1999 |accessdate=26 August 2013 }}</ref> Tal Blevins of IGN called it \"one of the best features\" of the game.<ref name=\"IGN\"/>\n\n''Grand Theft Auto 2''{{'}}s gameplay elements received mixed reactions. IGN's Jeremy Dunham said that the gameplay is \"where the game really takes a punch to the stomach\", and that it \"could've been a lot better.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://au.ign.com/articles/2000/05/09/grand-theft-auto-2-review |title=Grand Theft Auto 2 Review \u2013 IGN |last=Dunham |first=Jeremy |date=8 May 2000 |accessdate=26 August 2013 }}</ref> Tal Blevins called it \"simple, but effective.\"<ref name=\"IGN\"/> Jeff Gerstmann said that \"even though the gameplay is largely the same as in the previous ''GTA'', it's still a lot of fun.\"<ref name=\"GSpot\"/> ''[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]'' highlighted the game's story development and inventive missions, stating that ''Grand Theft Auto 2'' \"manages to draw you deep into the complexities of its world\".<ref name=\"Edge review\">{{cite magazine |title=Grand Theft Auto 2 |magazine=[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]] |publisher=[[Future Publishing]] |issue=79 |pages=80\u201381 |date=December 1999}}</ref>\n\nBlake Fischer reviewed the Dreamcast version of the game for ''[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]'', rating it two stars out of five, and stated that \"A great idea that, for one reason or another, never really gets into a must-play game.\"<ref name=\"NG\">{{cite magazine|last=Fischer|first=Blake|title=Finals|magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|volume=3|issue=8|publisher=[[Future US|Imagine Media]]|date=August 2000|page=90}}</ref>\n\n{{